subject: CS
title: Introduction to Computing: A Design and Development Perspective
description: Programming and problem solving using Python. Emphasizes principles of software development, style, and testing. Topics include procedures and functions, iteration, recursion, arrays and vectors, strings, an operational model of procedure and function calls, algorithms, exceptions, object-oriented programming. Weekly labs provide guided practice on the computer, with staff present to help.
notes_descrlong: Students in CS 1110 can register for an optional 1.0-credit Academic Excellence Workshop (AEW) to support their learning. AEWs are collaborative two-hour weekly problem-solving sessions led by peer educators who have previously taken this course. AEWs are designed to enhance understanding and deeper comprehension; you do not need to be an Engineering student to enroll. Grading is S/U. Search “ENGRG 1010” in the course catalog to learn more and enroll. | For Bowers Computer and Information Science (CIS) Course Enrollment Help, please see: https://tdx.cornell.edu/TDClient/193/Portal/Home/

Assignments can take a substantial amount of time, but try and find a smart partner and they will carry you.

subject: CS
course_full: cs 1110 introduction to computing using python
text:
This is one of the worst organized computer science classes I have ever taken. The material itself is not very hard, but it is extremely tedious and WILL NOT teach you how to code in python properly. In most assignments 90% of the coding for the "end goal" that they describe in the assignment description is done for you are you just need to fill in function definitions, making it hard to ever truly understand the bigger picture of the code that you are writing other than 5 to 10 lines before and after the one you're on. 
Almost all of the questions on exams and just in class are intentionally misleading and trick questions that teach you to understand specific mistakes that would almost never be made if you were to write the code yourself rather than how to actually build useful code overall. Throughout the semester there have been countless times where a certain way for a line to be written has been said BY THE LECTURER to be "bad coding" and something you should never do, and then for that exact same kind of coding to appear on an exam question just because it is confusing. This class would be really hard if I didn't have some background in Python coding already, and I wouldn't recommend it for anyone who actually wants to learn the language.

subject: CS

The lectures are confusing and teach concepts out of order, while the assignments are mainly 'pre-coded' for you where you have to add in code for yourself. This means that you don't ever code anything 100% by yourself, which means it's very difficult to understand concepts.

text: Took with Van Loan. Definitely easier than if taken with White (compared by workload with roommate's). As long as you're open to the programming mindset you should be fine.

subject: CS
course_full: cs 1110 introduction to computing using python
text: I loved the class. Walker's a wonderful professor and the tests are well-prepared. Be sure to do the past papers and assignments religiously and you should be fine.

subject: CS
course_full: cs 1110 introduction to computing using python
text: I was not a CS major and took it in a fall, too many CS egear freshman in the class so the curve was hard (so maybe don't take it in the fall if u are not a CS major). BUT it is an amazing class and I recommend everyone taking it.

subject: CS
course_full: cs 1110 introduction to computing using python
text: Great class! Especially with Walker White. Would recommend to any person of any study.

subject: CS
course_full: cs 1110 introduction to computing using python
text: Loved the class. Perfect introduction to Computer Science. Recommend taking with Walker in Fall.

subject: CS
course_full: cs 1110 introduction to computing using python
text: The class can be pretty difficult for people with no programming experience

subject: CS
course_full: cs 1110 introduction to computing using python
text: I really liked Walker, and the lectures were very much worth going to. Overall the class wasn't too difficult, but the later topics taught in class are a bit tricky.

subject: CS
course_full: cs 1110 introduction to computing using python
text: White is a great prof!! I highly suggest taking it in the fall with him

subject: CS
course_full: cs 1110 introduction to computing using python
text: Walker White is pretty good, but the class moves really fast if you don't have any programming experience.

subject: CS
course_full: cs 1110 introduction to computing using python
text: Walker is great, so take it in the Fall if you can. He pays a lot of attention to everyone in the class (S/U students, etc.), there are also lots of help available including long open consulting hours and Piazza where responses are super quick. The assignments are fun and rewarding as well. For lectures there is always Videonote, which makes lecture attendance non mandatory. The lab system can be taken online as well. So for me this course has turned into a de facto MOOC course :)

subject: CS
course_full: cs 1110 introduction to computing using python
text: Walker White is alright - I didn't get all the hype and fell asleep in lecture each day, but my ILR roommate who took the class and had no previous programming experience loved him.

subject: CS
course_full: cs 1110 introduction to computing using python
text: Definitely a fantastic introductory class when taken with White. I had some programming experience beforehand, so this class wasn't as hard for me but made a good GPA boost. If you're a CS major and have the ability to go to straight to 2110, you'd probably be fine to do so. But taking 1110 first is also a valid option if you want a bit of a grade boost and still learn some new concepts.

subject: CS
course_full: cs 1110 introduction to computing using python
text: I'm so glad I took this course with Walker White as my first exposure to CS, and he definitely swayed me into becoming a CS major. He was really engaging and organized the material very well. The assignments are fun and his lectures are really helpful! I would definitely recommend this class to anyone with the slightest interest in computer science.

subject: CS
course_full: cs 1110 introduction to computing using python
text: Great class. Walker convinced me to be a CS major

subject: CS
course_full: cs 1110 introduction to computing using python
text: Great professor! Definitely take it in the fall when walker white is teaching. This was my first experience with any cs or programming. I felt really overwhelmed at the beginning because it seemed like everyone else had prior experience but caught my footing pretty quickly. Definitely a class you need to put the work in for. One downside is that you are competing with people who took AP cs and just didn't get a 5, so it takes a bit of catching up. But definitely worth it. A class everyone should take.

subject: CS
course_full: cs 1110 introduction to computing using python
text: Yes, Walker White is a funny and clear professor. The work load is not too bad and the assignments are fun to do.

subject: CS
course_full: cs 1110 introduction to computing using python
text: Walker is an amazing professor, he makes everything easy to understand and keeps the class interesting.  The assignments can be tough but there are plenty of TA hours available, and they are always willing to answer questions on Piazza.

subject: CS
course_full: cs 1110 introduction to computing using python
text: Walker White's enthusiasm makes this an amazing introductory course! The topics are well paced, though the course if definitely a fair amount of work if you are new to coding. However, there are many resources in lab sections, TA and consultant office hours to help you!

subject: CS
course_full: cs 1110 introduction to computing using python
text: Walker White is the best. His lectures are very engaging and his assignments are quite fun. class is difficult if you have no prior experience with coding but not impossible if you put in the work. take this class in the fall so it's taught by Walker.

subject: CS
course_full: cs 1110 introduction to computing using python
text: Highly recommend to everyone (not just CS majors). I took it with Walker White and he gave phenomenal lectures that made concepts easy to understand even for people with no coding experience. Projects aren't too time consuming and are pretty fun!

subject: CS
course_full: cs 1110 introduction to computing using python
text: Take this with Professor Walker White. The lectures are very engaging, and the assignments are definitely a lot of work, but you learn a lot from them.

subject: CS
course_full: cs 1110 introduction to computing using python
text: Honestly such a great first introduction to Python! I had prior coding experience so my experience in this class might be different than others, but in my opinion, Walker White is really a great lecturer and there are many resources available to students. Not to mention the projects we get to work on are really fun and interesting!

subject: CS
course_full: cs 1998 freshmen and nontechnical team projects
text: Trends with DTI is really cool - made a fun project at the end of it. Pretty fun and helpful to learn about web development

subject: CS
course_full: cs 1998 freshmen and nontechnical team projects
text: (android course) Great course for learning the basics. Workload + difficulty was fair for 2 credits. Make sure to ask course staff if you get stuck, some projects are tricky to debug.

subject: CS
course_full: cs 1998 freshmen and nontechnical team projects
text: AppDev's Intro to iOS Development course gave me a lot of hands-on experience building something tangible that I could include in my resume/portfolio. The workload is significant for a 2-credit S/U course, but the instructors put effort into helping you pass, so it's a really good opportunity to learn without getting swamped by projects. Definitely worth every second spent.

subject: CS
course_full: cs 1998 freshmen and nontechnical team projects
text: AppDev's Introduction to iOS course is pretty palatable considering both the depth and breadth of content covered. It's an S/U course, and the instructors put in a lot of effort to help you pass, so even if the workload is too much at face value, there are still ways to learn a lot without going above and beyond. The Hack Challenge at the end was a good way to get hands-on experience working as a team, and helped me build something tangible for my portfolio.

subject: CS
course_full: cs 1998 freshmen and nontechnical team projects
text: I took Intro to Backend Development and found this course to be useful. Assignments don't take very long, and are well designed in terms of having you apply the concept of that week. Lectures and demos do not really go very in depth, but it's a good course if you're looking for an intro course that covers the basics.

subject: CS
course_full: cs 1998 freshmen and nontechnical team projects
text: I took Android and be prepared to spend A LOT of time every week. Basically spent all of my weekends. The first few projects were really frustrating, but I did learn a lot. The faculty is extremely helpful.

subject: CS
course_full: cs 1998 freshmen and nontechnical team projects
text: I took the backend class in fall 2019, and at the end of the class I didn't feel like I learned as much as I wanted to. I think some of the important concepts were explained very vaguely. The demos in class were very fast paced and hard to follow. The projects were long considering this was a 2 credit class. They were also hard to debug. The course instructors were very friendly and eager to help.

subject: CS
course_full: cs 1998 freshmen and nontechnical team projects
text: I am definitely glad I took it because I feel like I have a firm grasp on Swift now.  However, the course is definitely really time-consuming and each project takes a decent chunk of time (especially the final project) so just be aware.

subject: CS
course_full: cs 1998 freshmen and nontechnical team projects
text: I took the iOS course in the Spring of 2019. A solid class - enjoyable, project-based, everything I like out of a class that teaches you something new. Nothing like the format the CS classes I have taken thus far (namely, 2112 and 3110). I have a pretty strong programming background, so I completed the assignments quickly and with relative ease, but the course was time-consuming, especially considering how it's only offered pass-fail. Lectures are fast-paced, but all of them are recorded and posted on Piazza if you miss anything. Overall, it's definitely a worthwhile course if you have the time.

subject: CS
course_full: cs 1998 freshmen and nontechnical team projects
text: (regarding ios course) The course is a ton of work considering it's S/U, but since it's S/U you don't really need to do it all. Worth taking to learn Swift, the more seriously you take it the more you'll get it out of it. The lectures move very fast though and require work out of class to become proficient.

subject: CS
course_full: cs 1998 freshmen and nontechnical team projects
text: iOS project's are too time consuming for a pass/fail class. They have little to no instruction, are weekly, and it's unlike your typical CS class. It goes by fast and you will fall behind if you don't give it ur A game.

subject: CS
course_full: cs 2110 object-oriented programming and data structures
text: Both Mulherberger and Eichorn lectured very well and it was easy to understand content from lectures. Exams are fair (median ~70) and assignments usually aren't difficult but can be time consuming. Definitely learned a lot from this class and really enjoyed it.

subject: CS
course_full: cs 2110 object-oriented programming and data structures
text: Assignments weren't really that difficult, but did take me a significant amount of time (some parts of the assignment were SUPER hard for me to understand conceptually, but most of it was not bad). Exams were extremely difficult in my opinion. Feels like the professors try to connect 2+ confusing topics into one question, which makes it almost impossible for me to understand. That was my main struggle I would say is understanding questions that they designed to be complex and confusing, but I guess that just comes with the class.

subject: CS
course_full: cs 2110 object-oriented programming and data structures
text: Muhlberger is a verbose lecturer, but a nice guy. If you can get through the weeds, the content is all there.

subject: CS
course_full: cs 2110 object-oriented programming and data structures
text: Very fast paced. Pay attention to lectures.

subject: CS
course_full: cs 2110 object-oriented programming and data structures
text: Very easy. Start early on projects, reading is not needed, make sure you understand everything on the slides and take advantage of the study guides.

subject: CS
course_full: cs 2110 object-oriented programming and data structures
text: A very standard OOP class. Not the most fun, and assignments are pretty standard, but alright overall I guess.

subject: CS
course_full: cs 2110 object-oriented programming and data structures
text: Generally a very interesting and important class, especially to someone coming in without much prior formal CS knowledge. I was primarily self-studied before coming to Cornell, so this course was a great segway to the required CS curriculum! Muhlberger is generally a good teacher and has great slides.

subject: CS
course_full: cs 2110 object-oriented programming and data structures
text: I personally found Legunsen's lecture more entertaining and illustrative, whereas Muhlberger's were more fast-paced, articulate, and to-the-point. Both were great professors. This course provides plenty of resources to succeed, from the textbook to external notes to consulting/office hours pretty much every day.

subject: CS
course_full: cs 2110 object-oriented programming and data structures
text: Lots of resources available and the class information is very organized. Generally very flexible and I learned alot

subject: CS
course_full: cs 2110 object-oriented programming and data structures
text: I liked the overall structure of the course and lectures were generally informative. The projects were somewhat time-consuming, but they were good for practicing skills learned in lecture.

subject: CS
course_full: cs 2110 object-oriented programming and data structures
text: The lecture slides were very useful for review and all information was communicated very clearly for Prelim/Final review. Also the course content is very useful for interviews/etc.!

subject: CS
course_full: cs 2110 object-oriented programming and data structures
text: Goes over a lot of basics for CS that I can see the applications of in real life. Workload is somewhat heavy but makes sense for the content it covers.

subject: CS
course_full: cs 2110 object-oriented programming and data structures
text: Course could be quite challenging at times, and the lectures were not the most engaging. But, assignments were pretty cool and workload outside of those was not bad at all. Participation in lecture through iClicker is mandatory, as is discussion section. Also, the TAs for this class are super good and can help a lot

subject: CS
course_full: cs 2110 object-oriented programming and data structures
text: Projects were doable if you camp in office hours and start early! Exams were on the difficult side but there are a lot of resources given to help you study for the class. Material and concepts were harder than I thought.

subject: CS
course_full: cs 2110 object-oriented programming and data structures
text:
This class wasn't all too bad, however the lectures were pretty boring. It felt like a lot of the content in them was filler. There are mandatory readings, but no one keeps tabs as to whether you do them or not.

Overall, the workload wasn't terrible. There were quizzes every week that didn't take a heinous amount of time, and the coding assignments would take an average of 10-15 hours. On the weeks you didn't have to work on coding, you practically didn't have to do anything for the class.

subject: CS
course_full: cs 2110 object-oriented programming and data structures
text: rigorous but useful course

subject: CS
course_full: cs 2110 object-oriented programming and data structures
text: The course itself was not very difficult. I had no CS background before taking it (I taught myself Python to test out of CS 1110), but the material was never too challenging. The prelims were a little unpredictable, and the assignments also tended to take a while, but nothing too bad. The lectures were pretty long and boring and I always had trouble paying attention the whole time. Discussion sections were not very useful.

subject: CS
course_full: cs 2110 object-oriented programming and data structures
text: Course was well organized, lectures were clear and informative. Content gets pretty abstract for some ppl so def pay attention during lecture and read the textbooks and other resources provided. The assignments could get pretty hard but imo they were really fun to work through. Professors and TAs were very accessible via Ed discussion and responded to questions very quickly. Only complaint was that some exam questions were wacky and very abstract. I'm not a CS major, but I really enjoyed this class and am considering taking more CS classes in the future

subject: CS
course_full: cs 2110 object-oriented programming and data structures
text: If you have any prior programming experience, you'll be fine. I'd recommend learning the basics of Java before taking this course.

subject: CS
course_full: cs 2110 object-oriented programming and data structures
text: Took it with Myers and Muhlburger in FA' 22. Covered OOP principles I already knew, but were more in-depth and challenging. Also had a lot of new, interesting topics. Myers definitely made this class harder than it should've been. Labs were hastily prepared and usually somewhat challenging, but in the end, they taught me a lot and it overall was a good experience.

subject: CS
course_full: cs 2110 object-oriented programming and data structures
text: i'm an infosci major and my only previous experience was cs 1110 with anne bracy in sp22. apparently, cs 2110 was getting too easy so they brought in andrew myers (who usually teaches 2112) to make it more challenging, and yeah. it worked! the information is very important/useful but as someone with no java experience and who doesn't enjoy coding very much, i did not have a good experience. Exams were fair but the projects took way too long and office hours were too crowded to get sufficient help. beware non-cs majors!

subject: CS
course_full: cs 2110 object-oriented programming and data structures
text: Took this Spring 22. Gries and Clarkson were really great professors! This class was weirdly easier than 1110, and I struggled a lot in 1110. Lectures were paced well (not too fast/slow). Assignments were easier and shorter than 1110, but the assignments did get longer/harder as the course carried on. Exams were okay, do the practice prelims to study for them. Course organization could be a little confusing and there were frequent small canvas/CMS quizzes that need to be kept on top of - I tended to forget about them at the beginning of the semester. I enjoyed the humor Gries sprinkled in throughout his lectures, sad that he won't be teaching 2110 anymore!

subject: CS
course_full: cs 2110 object-oriented programming and data structures
text: Great professor. Good pool of resources and very useful content

subject: CS
course_full: cs 2110 object-oriented programming and data structures
text: As someone who really sucks at coding, this class was really hard. Because Gries' voice is so soothing, it's easy to fall asleep. However, the lectures are also somewhat disorganized and hard to understand. I ended up dropping the class for a W because I basically failed the second prelim. I had decided to drop the class and receive a W because I was also taking INFO 2300 at the same time, and was camping out office hours everyday for the final project, so I didn't have much time to study for CS 2110 in the first place.

subject: CS
course_full: cs 2110 object-oriented programming and data structures
text: I had Muhlberger and Myers. The class was good, interesting content especially in the latter half of the course. It is not too difficult if you have experience with Java from CSA. If you're going in with no Java experience it could be a little difficult at first. Overall content is fun, interesting, and relevant, but if you've already done basic LeetCode problems on data structures you may already know a lot of it.

subject: CS
course_full: cs 2110 object-oriented programming and data structures
text: I think this class is a really good introduction to cs and introduces a lot of important topics. Professor Gries is also a really good professor. The class isn't that much work other than the assignments.

subject: CS
course_full: cs 2110 object-oriented programming and data structures
text: I think that the amount of work for this class was appropriate given the credit total (I took this SP22).  The lecture materials are helpful in contributing to understanding. The exams however definitely more memorization than CS1110.

subject: CS
course_full: cs 2110 object-oriented programming and data structures
text: The content was APCS concepts but with extensions. The assignments didn't take long at all, and the tests were very fair. The practice exams are very helpful for preparing for the prelims. However, this course has since been revamped in Fall 2022, so the content of the course has significantly changed.

subject: CS
course_full: cs 2110 object-oriented programming and data structures
text: Took in Spring 2022. Clarkson is a very good lecturer. Material stacks up pretty quickly and goes by pretty fast so try not to get behind. Assignments are doable. Very important class if you are going into the SWE field. Exams are not too difficult as long as you understand the material well.

subject: CS
course_full: cs 2110 object-oriented programming and data structures
text: Good class

subject: CS
course_full: cs 2110 object-oriented programming and data structures
text: My first programming class was CS1110 so I often spent more time on the assignments than the mean and had a lot of trouble on the prelims. However, I would say I had an easier time than in CS1110.

subject: CS
course_full: cs 2110 object-oriented programming and data structures
text: David Gries is fun, but the course is mostly review if you have experience with Java or programming.

subject: CS
course_full: cs 2110 object-oriented programming and data structures
text: Great material and important to learn. Projects shorter and easier than CS 1110, but significantly harder exams.

subject: CS
course_full: cs 2110 object-oriented programming and data structures
text: Prof. Gries is amazing and I love the way he explains the materials! The course itself is challenging because it contains many new CS concepts!

subject: CS
course_full: cs 2110 object-oriented programming and data structures
text: good professor. will take again, sadly i will not be taking 2110 again.

subject: CS
course_full: cs 2110 object-oriented programming and data structures
text: The class is more so of an online class through my experience. I often don't go to lecture or recitations so I do most of the studying on my own time. There is of course many resources available to do this. But Gries and Clarkson are fair professors and the content is pretty interesting as well

subject: CS
course_full: cs 2110 object-oriented programming and data structures
text: I find myself doing lots of work alone because the lectures alone are not enough. Definitely is easier than CS1110 but also is way more boring. The assignments are doable. The prelims are hard-ish. There are random CMS/Canvas Quizzes too.

subject: CS
course_full: cs 2110 object-oriented programming and data structures
text: The content was really in depth but really fundamental towards developing an understanding towards core computer science fundamentals. The assignments were a bit more straight forward but really tested your understanding of the topics.

subject: CS
course_full: cs 2110 object-oriented programming and data structures
text: Very valuable class, was quite easy if you've taken AP CS A before, and seems reasonably doable even if you haven't.

subject: CS
course_full: cs 2110 object-oriented programming and data structures
text: A wide portion of the information you get from this class will be what you use in interviews. I thought the class was really fair but I knew Java from APCSA so that may make a difference.

subject: CS
course_full: cs 2110 object-oriented programming and data structures
text: I found the class material to be interesting and the things we learn are very applicable to the software engineering. The work for assignments is not as time consuming, but makes you think.

subject: CS
course_full: cs 2110 object-oriented programming and data structures
text: Good fundamental class.

subject: CS
course_full: cs 2110 object-oriented programming and data structures
text: Very little work throughout the semester and most of the time is spent learning concepts. For prelims, doing the past 3-4 years is helpful. Concepts you learn are important for SWE interviews.

subject: CS
course_full: cs 2110 object-oriented programming and data structures
text: This course goes over a lot of useful data structures and algos that will show up again in later courses. The one thing that I wish someone told me was that this class is strictly ALL memorization. Please just start making flashcards when you start learning data structures, you will thank yourself later. All the prelims will have really dumb definitions that you will just have to memorize for the prelim, and you will need to memorize specific algorithms that you need to write on the test. If you just memorize everything with flashcards you'll get an A.

subject: CS
course_full: cs 2110 object-oriented programming and data structures
text: His voice is too calming that I fall asleep in class. Other than that I really enjoy this class and the content.

subject: CS
course_full: cs 2110 object-oriented programming and data structures
text: The course was very well-run, as there were plenty of office hours to get help if needed. The professors were also very approachable and responded to ED discussions very quickly! However, the discussions felt disconnected from the course, and were often on subjects that were not related to exam material. Additionally, we had an optional final due to the COVID outbreak at the end of the fall semester 2021, which was very accommodating of the professors.

subject: CS
course_full: cs 2110 object-oriented programming and data structures
text: was gud

subject: CS
course_full: cs 2110 object-oriented programming and data structures
text: Interesting class, assignments were simple and fun (less work than CS 1110) and tests were on the easier side as well. The material was very interesting, goes in depth into some of the data structures, particularly graphs. The online Javahypertext book was a bit confusing to navigate.

subject: CS
course_full: cs 2110 object-oriented programming and data structures
text: Pretty good teacher, not the best. Workload wasn't that bad and were allowed partners. Biweekly quizzes were hard.

subject: CS
course_full: cs 2110 object-oriented programming and data structures
text: Taken Spring 2020. Assignments were not very time consuming. Course material was overall interesting, but concepts from lecture can be tough. They show up on exams, which I thought were the hardest part of the class.

subject: CS
course_full: cs 2110 object-oriented programming and data structures
text: The material is interesting, but Gries is a dry professor so the lectures can feel long. The class isn't too bad, the hardest part are the biweekly quizzes, but definitely doable. About 2-3. hours a week, mostly just watching lecture.

subject: CS
course_full: cs 2110 object-oriented programming and data structures
text: Took with David Gries in F19, and the class is not too exciting as it just goes through basics of java and object oriented programming. Took in person, and assignments take max a few hours. Lots of office hours support, and prelims are fine, just go to lectures. Go through past prelims as the prelims are very similar.

subject: CS
course_full: cs 2110 object-oriented programming and data structures
text: Assignments were easier than the ones from CS 1110. The biweekly quizzes are so hard for no apparent reason. You know it's bad when the prelim brings your grade up from them. Since it's Covid, I think they made the prelim harder cuz when I did prelim 1 I had no idea what was going on. Definitely should've studied more. Overall, it's pretty hard and you really need to study a lot for the prelims!

subject: CS
course_full: cs 2110 object-oriented programming and data structures
text: This class was thorough in teaching data structures in Java, and the workload was manageable.

subject: CS
course_full: cs 2110 object-oriented programming and data structures
text: All the class materials and resources were very accessible and nicely organized & presented. Biweekly quizzes were sometimes challenging but the assignments were fair. Profs. Gries and Muhlberger are both awesome and I learned a lot!

subject: CS
course_full: cs 2110 object-oriented programming and data structures
text: p nice!

subject: CS
course_full: cs 2110 object-oriented programming and data structures
text: Dr. Gries and Dr. Muhlberger were great. Lectures were clear and easy to follow. JavaHyperText is super useful. Beware: this class has a reputation of being "easy", but you get out of it as much as you put into it. The concepts are important for technical interviews. Do the reading and take notes! Don't skip lectures, especially in the latter half of the semester!

subject: CS
course_full: cs 2110 object-oriented programming and data structures
text: I found the lectures to be interesting and the assignments were short but instructive. Lectures were recorded on Panopto, I found some of their explanations to be confusing or lacking so rewatching or going to OH was helpful. Literally if you have any issue at all just go to OH and the answers will almost be fed to you. Gries isn't the best at explaining; the co-professor Curran Muhlberger was amazing at explaining things though

subject: CS
course_full: cs 2110 object-oriented programming and data structures
text: I personally did not find the content to be that engaging outside of some of the topics at the end of the course (such as Trees/Graphs and DFS/BFS). Concurrency/Theory of OOP in particular were not that interesting to me. That being said, I do think the assignments were worthwhile, and I would recommend this class to anyone who wants to learn more about Computer Science. Just don't expect this to be the holy grail of CS as it was described to me (though, tbf, I also don't do well with online education so take my review with a grain of salt).

subject: CS
course_full: cs 2110 object-oriented programming and data structures
text: great class

subject: CS
course_full: cs 2110 object-oriented programming and data structures
text: This class is awesome. I love professor Gries and Clarkson, but it should really be classified as a 4 credit class based on the workload we had. Very interesting content and I definitely learned a lot. Office hours are definitely your friend for coding assignments and exams are very similar to past prelims (the one we had before virtual lmao).

subject: CS
course_full: cs 2110 object-oriented programming and data structures
text: Basically all the topics in this class are pretty trivial, but youre going to get docked points for the most ridiculous things. This class doesn't train you to think, it trains to you to be a braindead software engineer that is only good for following directions.

subject: CS
course_full: cs 2110 object-oriented programming and data structures
text: Teaches a lot of very valuable/interesting stuff. The first half is basically just covering Java basics, so if you took APCS it's a lot of review. Lectures cover a lot of material and sometimes can go pretty fast.

subject: CS
course_full: cs 2110 object-oriented programming and data structures
text: I took it in Fall 2017. Weekly workload at most 5 hours a week for me. I got an A at the end.

subject: CS
course_full: cs 2110 object-oriented programming and data structures
text: Decent core class

subject: CS
course_full: cs 2110 object-oriented programming and data structures
text: Gries is great, but the class is way too easy

subject: CS
course_full: cs 2110 object-oriented programming and data structures
text: Assignments were less time-consuming compared to the ones from CS 1110, although it still took me a lot of time to finish them since CS 1110 was the only programming experience I had. A lot of the materials up to Prelim 1 overlapped with CS 1110 material, which I thought was a nice review. The lecture slides were pretty informative, and the lecturers were solid. Best part of this class was probably the optional final.

subject: CS
course_full: cs 2110 object-oriented programming and data structures
text: the lectures are helpful, but they only cover basics of what you need to know. so study things on your own

subject: CS
course_full: cs 2110 object-oriented programming and data structures
text: If you took AP Computer Science Java in high school the first part of this course up until the first prelim is very easy. After that it's data structures which I felt wasn't covered enough. Prelims are very easy as they give you all the past prelims to study from and the questions are rather repetitive so just memorize the answers and do a lot of them for practice. Assignments are relatively easy as well. I didn't need a partner. Only the last assignment really required some thinking.

subject: CS
course_full: cs 2110 object-oriented programming and data structures
text: Fall 2018, went in with no programming knowledge so there was a steep learning curve, but I learned a lot in the class and it made me really interested in CS

subject: CS
course_full: cs 2110 object-oriented programming and data structures
text: Great class! I love the way the two professors teach the content. The workload is practically negligible.

subject: CS
course_full: cs 2110 object-oriented programming and data structures
text: I took it in Fall 2018. The class is very helpful for job interviews.

subject: CS
course_full: cs 2110 object-oriented programming and data structures
text: This class was reasonably hard, but really helpful. The professors did an okay job teaching it and there were a lot of course assistant.
professors: David Gries, Douglas James, Siddhartha Chaudhuri

subject: CS
course_full: cs 2110 object-oriented programming and data structures
text: Similar conceptual difficulty to 1110, but the assignments were a lot easier. If anything, working with a partner would probably slow you down since the assignments are so short.

subject: CS
course_full: cs 2110 object-oriented programming and data structures
text: Easy class with almost no work (seven project that took me less than 3 hours usually). Well taught for the most part, but you do have to study for the exams since there's a lot of annoying, very specific details that come up.

subject: CS
course_full: cs 2110 object-oriented programming and data structures
text: I found the class to be the hardest class I have ever taken at Cornell, and I am in engineering and have taken classes like math 1920 and Chem 2090 (those two were also hard for me but they were not as bad as 2110). I found the clsss to be disorganized and the lectures to be boring. I also had trouble with every single project and had a hard time finding good help. I am sure that the materials are helpful for CS majors (or minors), and they proabbly could be interesting if you like it. But as someone who is not a CS person, I really struggled in the class and did not have a good time :((

subject: CS
course_full: cs 2110 object-oriented programming and data structures
text: I took with Gries and Bracy, FA18. The class itself is good, with fun assignments that were good at teaching you new concepts. Gries is a keyboard warrior on Piazza, whose comments can be rather rude and unnecessary at times, but I do think he tries to be helpful most of the time. For me, the assignments were very doable, but they're curved with the rest of the class, so even if you do well (average around 90%), it will be like a B on your overall homework grade. This means exams almost entirely constitute your average, which sucks since the exams were really nitpicky. STUDY THE PAST EXAMS! They will help a lot.

subject: CS
course_full: cs 2110 object-oriented programming and data structures
text: it's hard to fail this class. they have a boat load of practice prelims on the website and the final is optional. median grades for assignments are high. the content is really useful for CS interviews and it was interesting to me imo

subject: CS
course_full: cs 2110 object-oriented programming and data structures
text: Assignments dont take too long (4-6 hrs), and I would recommend taking as many practice prelims as you can if you are aiming for an A.

subject: CS
course_full: cs 2110 object-oriented programming and data structures
text: A really easy class with a doable amount of work, usually spend less than 3 hours on each assignment

subject: CS
course_full: cs 2110 object-oriented programming and data structures
text: Not difficult (you can put in minimal effort and get by), but there is a lot of important information to learn for later CS classes.

subject: CS
course_full: cs 2110 object-oriented programming and data structures
text: Great class to take. Took it Spring 2018. You will learn a lot about the basics of computer science and become familiar with java/oo programming. Projects take a max of 10 hours and are normally around 5-6 hours long. Lectures aren't necessary, as long as you read the lecture notes and are comfortable with the projects. Prelims are fair, but very small mistakes can mean the difference between an A and B. Make sure to study the finer details of the lecture notes.

subject: CS
course_full: cs 2110 object-oriented programming and data structures
text: Class was pretty straightforward, in many ways just a direct duplication/slight extension of concepts covered in AP CS. Gries is one of the most committed professors and while he may be difficult if you ask questions that he deems to be unimportant, if you actually seek him out and demonstrate a willingness to learn, he is truly fantastic. I stopped attending lectures after week 2, I definitely think you can look at the syllabus and just go to lectures on concepts you aren't familiar with.

subject: CS
course_full: cs 2110 object-oriented programming and data structures
text: Not taught super well and felt pretty disorganized. This is reflected strongly in the prelims which ask a lot of obscure knowledge. The projects were good though and not super stressful if you find a good partner. Helps a ton if you already know OOP despite what the professors say, simply because they don't teach it well at all and being familiar with it beforehand means you don't have to rely on the lectures as much. Would recommend learning a bit beforehand (APCS is enough prep).

subject: CS
course_full: cs 2110 object-oriented programming and data structures
text: The instructions are often vague (maybe on purpose, i have no idea) and requires a lot of efforts on our own end; for instance, incompatibilities in given code and recitations where the problem makes little sense (the task needs not be done at all or should not be implemented this way). The second Prelim contains way too much mechanical recitation (3 steps to monitor GUI events) which we should look up in API in real practice. The assignments appear too problem-set like, in lieu of fun practical projects like we had in Python.

subject: CS
course_full: cs 2110 object-oriented programming and data structures
text: Learned a lot in this class but the exams were pretty challenging. Assignments were doable if you start early. The semester I took it (Spring 2016), Gries curved it so low that even if you were at the mean raw score for the class you ended up with a C+. I don't think it's happened in other semesters but that really sucked.

subject: CS
course_full: cs 2110 object-oriented programming and data structures
text: The content is extremely interesting and important - loved the course content. However, the structure isn't really a structure. The class is very disorganized and the content is spread in different places, with no clear grading guidelines. Piazza is unhelpful and Gries can be condescending. I would have had the best time if the course was better structured. You basically teach yourself everything.

subject: CS
course_full: cs 2110 object-oriented programming and data structures
text: If you took 1110 and did decent the first half of 2110 is basically reviewing what you learned in Python and is really easy. The projects are also relatively low in terms of time commitment and difficulty. If you did not enjoy 1110 and don't have to take 2110, don't do it because it's not super interesting compared to 1110. If you took MATLAB before 2110, expect this class to be hard for you. Also, if you take this class you can understand the Gries memes so why not!

subject: CS
course_full: cs 2110 object-oriented programming and data structures
text: Gries lectures weren't very helpful. The first half of the class is learning to use java syntax instead of python/matlab. Second half of the class I found to be very interesting. Prelims can be difficult, best way to study for them is by doing practice prelims as the types of questions and formats generally don't change.

subject: CS
course_full: cs 2110 object-oriented programming and data structures
text: Gries was condescending and the prelims are incredibly hard. Lecture material does not prepare you at all for assignments or prelims.

subject: CS
course_full: cs 2110 object-oriented programming and data structures
text: Wow this class was so hard but also so interesting.

subject: CS
course_full: cs 2110 object-oriented programming and data structures
text: I took this in Spring 2016. Content itself is very useful for the computer science major as it is the foundation of all interviews. However, I found the projects to be tedious and useless, and lectures were extremely boring with Foster and Gries.

subject: CS
course_full: cs 2110 object-oriented programming and data structures
text: Loved this class! Incredibly important for interviews later in college, and Gries is great. Really enjoyed the "lunch with professors" he did.

subject: CS
course_full: cs 2110 object-oriented programming and data structures
text: Gries is the best! funny jokes and genuinely cares about how well students are learning

subject: CS
course_full: cs 2110 object-oriented programming and data structures
text: Great class! I reference the lecture slides for this class when TAing other classes. good content

subject: CS
course_full: cs 2110 object-oriented programming and data structures
text: Not an extremely difficult class but I made the mistake of chilling too much thinking that the class would be easy. Make sure you go to every single class. A lot of the material that shows up on the exam IS covered in lectures but if you try to cram everything simply by doing practice tests or reading slides, you will not catch those small details. Work your hardest on assignments - they often dock points for little details you might not have caught even if your program works fine. Recitations are not necessarily as useful but I would go anyways because certain topics do get covered. Usually I wouldn't suggest to take final regardless of your grade so you should know your grade after the second prelim basically. I find the curve pretty generous as well. Also the second prelim is really really hard compared to the first one.

subject: CS
course_full: cs 2110 object-oriented programming and data structures
text: The projects given are fairly simple, but the directions are vague and you will lose points as a result.

subject: CS
course_full: cs 2110 object-oriented programming and data structures
text: Lectures are very helpful in this class! Definitely a great introduction to object-oriented programming, and helped me get a sophomore internship for the summer. The material is pretty interesting and the workload isn't bad.

subject: CS
course_full: cs 2110 object-oriented programming and data structures
text: Interesting course material and projects, lectures optional

subject: CS
course_full: cs 2110 object-oriented programming and data structures
text: Gries is a good professor, but attendance isn't really required.

subject: CS
course_full: cs 2110 object-oriented programming and data structures
text: it was easy to get good grades on the projects without knowing much and then you were screwed for exams. definitely spend should've spent more time on it

subject: CS
course_full: cs 2110 object-oriented programming and data structures
text: Gries is a really great professor, but grading can be unforgiving sometimes. most importantly, DO NOT TAKE THE OPTIONAL FINAL EXAM. It is much much harder than the prelims and will most likely lower your grade.

subject: CS
course_full: cs 2110 object-oriented programming and data structures
text: This class was a good introduction into computer science/programming as a whole. Looking back, I wish I had gone to more lectures, as I now often refer to the lecture notes from it. The skills you learn in this class are extremely marketable, and I've had several recruiters for software developer companies tell me that their interviews for sophomores from Cornell are based completely on the material covered in CS 2110. The projects were also extremely fun, and not too challenging or time consuming.

subject: CS
course_full: cs 2800 discrete structures
text: I greatly enjoyed the content, but this class was weakened by disorganized teaching. Combinatorics and sets were super interesting and the tricks were fun. Probability has its own tricks and is applicable to ML and so many modern applications. I enjoyed being able to jump from one topic to another. However, the lectures were increasingly unhelpful, often devolving into literal handwaving or incomprehensible scribbling. Eichhorn’s notes were much better. Grading was nitpicky grading, and there were often mistakes in grading exams.

subject: CS
course_full: cs 2800 discrete structures
text: Tardos was hard to understand and would mess up during lecture and tell the class to refer to the book instead.   Grading was harsh.

subject: CS
course_full: cs 2800 discrete structures
text: Pretty chill. It’s a math class, no coding involved. Good intro to proofs. Matt is a really good prof

subject: CS
course_full: cs 2800 discrete structures
text: Anke was a great professor, she’s very good at explaining difficult content and although the p-sets were challenging, I always felt there was good support from lecture notes. The p-sets are very time consuming though so it’s good start early. Definitely recommend taking with Anke!

subject: CS
course_full: cs 2800 discrete structures
text:
Learned a lot and good intro for writing proofs. 
But probability unit felt a bit rushed. True and false on prelims was hard.

subject: CS
course_full: cs 2800 discrete structures
text: Best professor I have had at Cornell so far. He was always very engaging and helpful in lecture. The homework were somewhat challenging but very helpful in learning the material and preparing for exams. Also the practice exams were very indicative of the actual exams.

subject: CS
course_full: cs 2800 discrete structures
text: Lectures in this course were pretty disorganized and unhelpful overall; by the end they got better but both professors gave somewhat winding and hard-to-follow lectures which made it difficult to be excited about this course. Exams were also pretty difficult, not unreasonably so but enough to mess with me. Other than that, this course wasn't bad: office hours and discussion sections were relatively helpful and homework was really effective for helping me understand course content on my own. Eichhorn's lecture note textbook was really good as well, concise and interesting. But the lectures kinda ruined it -- it made it difficult to enjoy the course.

subject: CS
course_full: cs 2800 discrete structures
text: This was definitely one of the hardest classes I have taken at Cornell but also really interesting. The p-sets take forever but office hours helped a lot and I got a really good understanding of the concepts. Matt was also an amazing professor and explained the concepts really well in lecture. Also amazing TAs!

subject: CS
course_full: cs 2800 discrete structures
text: It was a very well organized course, provides broad introduction to important theoretical topics in CS.

subject: CS
course_full: cs 2800 discrete structures
text:
Taking it with Joseph Halpern and Eva Tardos in Spring '25. (Not sure of grade yet, so I just put B-)

This class was one of the worst academic experiences I've ever had (even though I would say I'm decently good at math, having taken graduate-level math before coming to Cornell) and actively makes me consider switching to Info Sci every time I have to do the problem sets.

Proofs are a central component of the course, but the professors rarely demonstrate valid proofs in lecture— they only do proof "sketches"/summaries, but the homeworks require actual proofs, so we have to fend for ourselves on the homeworks. It's pretty much required to camp office hours to get a good grade on the homeworks, unless you happen to be a math prodigy or have previous experience with math competitions.

Furthermore, the course Canvas is very unorganized and makes it hard to find the information you need at any given time.

subject: CS
course_full: cs 2800 discrete structures
text: Matt is a really good professor, but the homework and exams were super difficult. He's definitely the best professor you can have for this class though since I've heard the others are worse

subject: CS
course_full: cs 2800 discrete structures
text: I thought this class was harder than algo tbh, but I didn't have any theoretical math proof experience coming in. I struggled to understand how to write proofs and they all had to be roughly structured a certain way. Anke was amazing and so incredibly sweet, as were the TAs in OH. I did enjoy the content in the class, but wasn't able to complete the HWs (or even prelims) without guidance.

subject: CS
course_full: cs 2800 discrete structures
text: I liked the content taught in course. Professor is passionate about the material. A lot of work is involved but if you pay attention and attend OH, you will be fine.

subject: CS
course_full: cs 2800 discrete structures
text: Matt is a great professor. Workload is reasonable

subject: CS
course_full: cs 2800 discrete structures
text: Pretty difficult class but doable. Psets are tough and exams are a bit tougher but 2800 was alright overall. I think Anke is also quite a decent lecturer and there was a class shirt up for sale at the end which was pretty cool.

subject: CS
course_full: cs 2800 discrete structures
text: Discussion section is a must for this class to reinforce the things that you learn in lecture... they are also mandatory. Anke is a great professor who makes the concepts as clear as possible, but this is definitely challenging for people like me who have not had experience with proof-based mathematics. A lot of interesting topics covered that are useful for CS majors.

subject: CS
course_full: cs 2800 discrete structures
text:
Starting off, I'd like to say that the professor was very sweet. She was very open to feedback and definitely has a lot of experience with the field.

The class however, is the hardest I've taken so far. As someone without any competitive math experience and scarce opportunities in my high school, at times the work felt near impossible. I attended office hours 2-3 days a week and still the homework's were very challenging to understand. There are plenty of resources in this class, which is an amazing plus, but without that experience it's hard for it to click.

At least for me, it was a lot of time spent staring at the problems without any answers popping up wherein people who'd done these types of problems before could at least formulate a pathway.

You'll do just fine if you have a lot of prior math experience, but sadly that wasn't the case for me.

There was a quiz, two prelims, and a final for this class. We also had weekly homework, plus reading resources if we needed them.

subject: CS
course_full: cs 2800 discrete structures
text: A great rigorous introduction to subjects you've probably encountered in idle mathematical exploration up till college

subject: CS
course_full: cs 2800 discrete structures
text: Overall an interesting class, but very difficult. I made the mistake of not attending office hours for the weekly problem sets, which meant I would spend upwards of 15 hours on them each week. Studying for the tests was very time consuming. However, the exams were always identical in structure to the practice ones, and a good review sheet was always given, so it was easy to do well on them as long as you studied hard. However, the material was very hard to grasp at first, but became easier as the semester progressed. Need a good partner to work through this class or else you make it very hard on yourself.

subject: CS
course_full: cs 2800 discrete structures
text: I took this class with Noah Stephens-Davidowitz and Matt Eichhorn. The lectures were sometimes a little dry, and sometimes they ran out of time and you had to study the material on your own (they wouldn't push anything over into the next lecture). The prelims were pretty easy (and there were great practice tests), but the problem sets could be fairly challenging and tended to take up quite a bit of time.

subject: CS
course_full: cs 2800 discrete structures
text: Took last SP '23 with Anke and Renee. They were good lecturers and explained things pretty well, but the weekly problem sets and exams are pretty challenging (especially if you're new to proofs). Gotta do what you gotta do though

subject: CS
course_full: cs 2800 discrete structures
text: A truly incredible course. Very challenging but extremely rewarding. Influenced the way I think about mathematics and problem solving and helped me tons for future courses. If you take this course, make sure to give it your best effort because if you do, you will come out of the course a better problem solver, which is one of the most important skills as a STEM major. Lots of work but the reward is definitely worth it.

subject: CS
course_full: cs 2800 discrete structures
text: Loved having Anke as a professor, she's seriously so nice. This class was just stupid hard and I didn't understand discrete at all. I felt like I was drowning just trying to get the HW done for the weekly deadlines. HW always required OH for me, and OH were often PACKED. They seriously need a bigger room for it, people ended up sitting on the floor/standing because there were no chairs left. I came into this class with no background in theoretical/proof math or competition math, which sorely hurt I think. Tried to get partial credit on exams but still did poorly on them and ended up dropping the class. Definitely a weed out class for CS

subject: CS
course_full: cs 2800 discrete structures
text: Decent course, lectures could be a little confusing sometimes, but liked the content and the applications covered. Course was harder/more in-depth than previous semesters, and office hours were busy, but enjoyed the course overall. Difficult final.

subject: CS
course_full: cs 2800 discrete structures
text: The course starts off pretty heavy with a lot of proofs and math you haven't seen before which makes it intimidating at first, but as you go on the topics get more specific but not as difficult. Suggested that you go to office hours to complete weekly psets

subject: CS
course_full: cs 2800 discrete structures
text: Personally, I don't really like the class because of it's proof-based. The lecture notes are easy to catch up with lectures (reading those is even better than going to lecture). However, the profs is super INFLEXIBLE in term of everything! If you submit a homework on time but in wrong place, you will receive a zero no matter what and they don't really often adapt your need. Moreover, the homework is much harder than the example in the lecture notes.

subject: CS
course_full: cs 2800 discrete structures
text: I really liked the professor. For this class, I feel like if you put in the effort, you'll be able to do well. The content itself is different from any other class I've taken - a lot of it is proofs.

subject: CS
course_full: cs 2800 discrete structures
text: The lectures were well taught and very organized. The professor is definitely really nice too! There is definitely a lot of content covered and can be really confusing - especially in the beginning. The psets are really difficult and time consuming, so I would start early.

subject: CS
course_full: cs 2800 discrete structures
text: Concepts are not covered well in class. The psets were so hard that it was basically a requirement to camp office hours in order to do well on them. Need a group of friends to work on psets with, otherwise ur screwed.

subject: CS
course_full: cs 2800 discrete structures
text: This is a pretty difficult course for people with no prior experience with proofs but the topics are quite interesting. I had new professors Alexandra Silva and Matt Eichorn. I think people saw them like an angel (Matt) devil (Silva) combo but honestly both of them are good lecturers. The content can be tough so office hours are always useful.

subject: CS
course_full: cs 2800 discrete structures
text: The class was well organized but I feel I should've paid more attention but couldn't because it was very theory-heavy.

subject: CS
course_full: cs 2800 discrete structures
text: Homeworks are hard, lectures are a little boring, the notes are good. The prelims are a lot easier than the homeworks. A lot of work if it is the first of its class you are taking.

subject: CS
course_full: cs 2800 discrete structures
text: Professor Alexandra Silva and Matt are the most INHUMANE instructors I have had so far. They made me submit problem sets while I was in the hospital barely clinging to my consciousness, with my SDS as well. And when I missed a problem set because I was sick and I was in the hospital, they stone cold rejected my and my advisor's request to extend the deadline. DO NOT TAKE THEIR CLASS, apart from them being inhumane they are also extremely bad at teaching!

subject: CS
course_full: cs 2800 discrete structures
text:
This class is extremely difficult for: people with no competitive math experience, people with basic high school math knowledge, and people who did not previously study discrete structures. If you fall under these categories as I did, you are in for a ride. The psets were long and difficult, and almost always required you to go to OH. The prelims are difficult, my main objective at least was to get the most partial credit as possible because it was impossible for me to get full credit on any question.

There used to be a separate honors discrete class for those who already had a strong mathematical background, but without this class there were a lot of people "breaking" the curve because they already knew the material.

The course content is interesting, but this is an extremely demanding class!

subject: CS
course_full: cs 2800 discrete structures
text: Really hope that a place-out option could be provided for math majors who have taken upper level courses in  math.  Never went to lectures and never learned anything useful. This course is completely a waste of time.

subject: CS
course_full: cs 2800 discrete structures

subject: CS
course_full: cs 2800 discrete structures
text: This class was very engaging and well structured!

subject: CS
course_full: cs 2800 discrete structures

subject: CS
course_full: cs 2800 discrete structures

subject: CS
course_full: cs 2800 discrete structures

subject: CS

subject: CS

subject: CS
course_full: cs 2800 discrete structures
text: Liked the professor. Well organized lectures. Course staff was good, not great. Discussion sections were stale and did not help lecture. I believe it is a highly inequitable class. That being said, I did enjoy the material.

subject: CS
course_full: cs 2800 discrete structures
text: Professor van Zuylen was an organized lecturer. Problem sets are useful in preparing for exams, especially if you take the time to think through them on your own. If you have never written proofs before, it might be hard in the beginning to get used to the format.

subject: CS
course_full: cs 2800 discrete structures
text: Taken during F19, and lectures are boring and go through a single proof the whole lecture. Topics are not fun and the idea is to learn proof techniques, but the class is slow and the homework requires office hours as that is not gone over during class. Prelims are  similar to homework level, so make sure to go over all those problems before the prelims.

subject: CS
course_full: cs 2800 discrete structures
text: The class is significantly better with van Zuylen. She's a great professor and holds excellent lectures. I thought exams were fair and homeworks were usually useful in solidifying concepts.

subject: CS
course_full: cs 2800 discrete structures
text: Professor was Anke van Zuylen but since she's new, I guess she's not a listed option yet. I heard that this class was difficult and was nervous about taking it, but Professor van Zuylen was excellent and very understanding with remote students. Lectures were clear and engaging. They had plenty of examples. Course staff was helpful.  I personally did not think office hours were necessary to complete the homework, but many people did.

subject: CS
course_full: cs 2800 discrete structures
text: If you don't have a strong background in mathematical proofs & discrete math, then you might spend a considerable amount of time trying to comprehend things, being that it is not really about physical coding. However, the class functions as a foundation for future upper level courses, so it is definitely worth investing your time. Also, Prof. Michael is really accomodating & willingly explains concepts, so don't hesitate to ask questions!

subject: CS
course_full: cs 2800 discrete structures
text: I am taking it this semester, the homework is difficult but it is really fun since they require a lot of out-of-the-box thinking.

subject: CS
course_full: cs 2800 discrete structures
text: The website is basically chicken scratch, and I really have to dig to find good examples of proofs for specific topics. Some examples are not even available. The office hours are way to0 crowded, and they are optional for TAs!!! The PSets are way too hard because you basically have to LIVE at office hours. The TAs can't tell you if you're doing something correctly because they're not allowed to. Everything is chicken scratch and I'm lost and gonna fail the class.

subject: CS
course_full: cs 2800 discrete structures
text: It's hard. It's required. It's depressing. But, I cannot deny the fact that it is somewhat well-taught and the professor actually gives a toss about your difficulties. The lectures are delivered in a sensible manner and his explanation is thorough; the textbook was almost completely absent from my routine but his online wiki more than make up for my learning process. However, the homework is cleverly written and a b**** to do, and the smug man knows it. It is absolutely the most difficult homework I have encountered at Cornell thus far and you are better off waiting for answers and explanations at OH than doing it with your partner or alone, and it doesn't help you to prepare for prelims and finals as those questions are hard but nowhere as tricky and tedious. Overall, this course is acceptable but it can definitely be more reasonable about its difficulty, but then it has "weed-out" written all over it so I am not surprised. Anybody who says it isn't hard is a flexing tryhard.

subject: CS
course_full: cs 2800 discrete structures
text: Didn't like the subjects but i liked michael george

subject: CS
course_full: cs 2800 discrete structures
