subject: CS
course_full: cs 2800 discrete structures
text: The course content is very interesting and the homework serves well on purpose of helping understanding concepts in the lecture. However, the discussion session (which I attend) is basically a waste of time.

subject: CS
course_full: cs 2800 discrete structures
text: I think this course is ok but maybe it will be better if there are more proof examples instead of proof ideas, and I wish we get similar structured practice prelims instead of just some not similar related problems.

subject: CS
course_full: cs 2800 discrete structures
text: Problem sets take too long and require office hours to get anywhere near the median grade.

subject: CS
course_full: cs 2800 discrete structures
text: Everyone complains about this course, but I thought it was ok. Most of it was interesting, some boring/annoying/pedantic. Much of the material was new to me - and I've done competition math but little formal (proofy) math, whereas this course is very focused on the formal/proof stuff - and I felt like the lectures were at an appropriate level. The workload was 8-10 hours per week; it basically felt like a 4-credit class (it's a 3-credit class). Michael George explains stuff well and tries to make the material relevant from both a math-CS and an industry-CS perspective.

subject: CS
course_full: cs 2800 discrete structures
text: Worst class I've taken in CS. The concepts are not covered well in class or the textbook, and the problem sets are so hard that you are required to go to office hours, unless you've had prior exposure to the topics in the class.

subject: CS
course_full: cs 2800 discrete structures
text: This is a great course and Professor George explains everything clearly. All you need to do is to pay attention in the class and takes notes carefully. Homework could be difficult sometimes, but office hour is really helpful. I don't understand why the score for quality is so low, but this course do prepare you for proving things seriously and later CS classes.

subject: CS
course_full: cs 2800 discrete structures
text: I took this class with Professor George in Fall 2018 with no prior discrete math experience. This class took some time for me to get used to, as I was not doing as well as I wanted up until the end of Prelim 1. Looking back, the material was pretty interesting. However, I feel like I gained much more from completing the homework and going to (too many) office hours than Professor George's lectures. On the bright side, there are many TAs available for this course, and I have had exceptional experiences with all but one of my office hour visits. One tip: Besides going to office hours, don't stress too much about the prelims. I almost dropped this class after the first one, but it turned out that I did much better than I thought, leading me to do very well on the final.

subject: CS
course_full: cs 2800 discrete structures
text: The topics for the class is extensive. But, a lot of the difficult concepts were covered almost at the end of the semester that I felt like there was not much opportunity for us to practice what we learned before finals.

subject: CS
course_full: cs 2800 discrete structures
text: I have TA-d for the course for multiple semesters. I think the course content was easy for me, but I had some background in discrete math and extensive background in proof-writing. With that being said, I think the course is fairly mediocre/in some sense bad at truly covering discrete math and some of the topics like DFAs/regexs/proof trees should not be in a discrete math course (even if it is called discrete structures). Also, grading is fairly mediocre, with internal rubrics in some sense being pattern-matching based and problems tend to not require legitimate understanding and just knowing the general idea is enough to get a fairly significant number of points.

subject: CS
course_full: cs 2800 discrete structures
text: Median grade has been a B+ for the last few semesters. Didn't like Professor George's lectures at all. I'm not alone in this opinion; most people stopped showing up or were asleep in class. Material was actually interesting, but unfortunately was not presented and explained well.

subject: CS
course_full: cs 2800 discrete structures
text: Really hard to pay attention unless you're good with proofs/theoretical math because Michael George moves really fast in lectures. If you're like me and can't follow what happens your best bet is to study it out of class. Exams are hard but you can do okay if you know how to get partial credit on questions. Homeworks are super hard unless you go to OH and get all the answers (almost everyone gets 100s on them so you pretty much need to). If you like math you'll like this course, if you don't you won't. Not worth quitting the major over this though so just power through it.

subject: CS
course_full: cs 2800 discrete structures
text: This class, despite the difficulty, is actually quite fun. Michael George is an excellent teacher, and is clear and helpful during most of the lectures (I agree some of them are harder to understand). The first prelim was alright, the second pretty nasty, and final a breeze. If you really do the homework yourself and understand the problems thoroughly you will be fine.

subject: CS
course_full: cs 2800 discrete structures
text: This class is legit the class that forces young CS majors into INFO. Don't take it unless you have to. If you can power through this and get at least a C+ to affiliate with the CS major though, don't give up because this is the actual worst class you will ever have to take otherwise. The problem sets aren't bad if you go to the right office hours but the exams are legit out of 30 points and absurdly hard. Requires a ton of work and is the most disorganized and disinteresting lecture ever.

subject: CS
course_full: cs 2800 discrete structures
text: The class is not easy, but the material is cool and office hours or smart friends makes the class very doable.

subject: CS
course_full: cs 2800 discrete structures
text: be ready to camp out at office hours :(

subject: CS
course_full: cs 2800 discrete structures
text: I'm not the greatest at math (actually I don't like it very much at all--why am I in engineering again?), and 2800 has definitely been a challenge for me, but I have been enjoying the material covered in this class. There's something beautiful about proofs even if I can't recreate them myself. I'm taking CS 2110 and Math 2940 concurrently with 2800, and the material often overlaps, which is kinda cool (everything's connected!) I personally find Prof. George an adequate lecturer. He's pretty generous about deadlines and takes into consideration student feedback/performance. Office hours are a must for the time-consuming problem sets, but if you go, it's pretty easy to get most of the hw points. I would say the support from TAs/Piazza is pretty good too. Overall, even if you aren't very good at math like me, you can still do reasonably well and find this class rewarding provided that you put in the work and effort.

subject: CS
course_full: cs 2800 discrete structures
text: Mike George is not a great teacher; he's extremely caring, but he just can't teach the material well enough for the majority of the class to understand. This is much more of a math class than CS, so I personally struggled with it, but if you're good at discrete math then you'll love this class. You either love it or hate it. Just be prepared to do a LOT of proofs and logic, and no CS :( Not work intensive (1 pset / week) but expect to spend a lot of time in office hours if you're not the greatest at discrete math.

subject: CS
course_full: cs 3110 data structures and functional programming
text: Mohan is a nice guy who really likes what he’s teaching. I guess some of the assignments were fun, and it was cool to see the functional perspective on programming. The data structures were fun to learn and implement using this mathy language. However, I wish the teaching of OCaml was motivated more beyond “it’s cool!” because the exams were unfortunately largely an annoying test of memorizing OCaml syntax. There weren't enough data structures, making this more of a “learn OCaml!” class.

subject: CS
course_full: cs 3110 data structures and functional programming
text: Weekly projects were very time consuming.

subject: CS
course_full: cs 3110 data structures and functional programming
text: The lectures are clear and well-organized though a bit boring. The workload for the course is generally ok, though some assignments are stressful and can take a long time. The professor is very enthusiastic about the material.

subject: CS
course_full: cs 3110 data structures and functional programming
text: Very manageable class. Assignments were very interesting

subject: CS
course_full: cs 3110 data structures and functional programming
text: this class is super rewarding because you’ll basically master a completely new language in just one semester. professor mohan is a bit of a stickler but a very good lecturer. as a warning to future students, please read the programming guidelines…

subject: CS
course_full: cs 3110 data structures and functional programming
text: Lowkey easier than 2110, very nice professor, workload was high but not super high

subject: CS
course_full: cs 3110 data structures and functional programming
text: This course to me is quite well taught but simply the content was not that interesting to me. Mohan is a sometimes humorous lecturer and pretty energetic, which depending on the day is funny or annoying. Overall, the course is pretty easy to follow and you learn a decent amount, if you're interested in functional programming. But OCaml is kind of a sucky language.

subject: CS
course_full: cs 3110 data structures and functional programming
text: Prof. Mohan is my goat. He's one of the sweetest and most passionate professors I've ever had -- every time I walked into class his excitement to teach was palpable, and the course itself was pretty well-balanced and fun which helped. Assignments were very nicely graded and occasionally difficult but usually alright, and exams were in-class with cheat sheets allowed so I didn't sweat them that hard. Also, OCaml is an incredibly fun language to learn and mess around with and I had a lot of fun with it.

subject: CS
course_full: cs 3110 data structures and functional programming
text:
The lecture and the content are extremely engaging and important for a computer science career. 

The assignments allows a lot of creativity and flexibilities, which encourages a lot of exploration.

The professor is passionate and helpful always.

subject: CS
course_full: cs 3110 data structures and functional programming
text:
I loved this class! Possibly the best class I've ever taken at Cornell to be honest. 3110 really forces you to approach coding in a different way and you find out just how elegant and neat functional programming can be — I genuinely found a new appreciation for CS even as someone who is not super passionate about it. Assignments are super interesting too — definitely the most fun I've ever had in a CS class. It really feels like you're learning and applying cool new things every time you complete a new assignment.

We had assignments every week that normally took from 6-10 hours, so quite a lot of work, however, they were graded out of 85 so as long as you reach 85 it's automatically 100%.

Attendance is graded but you can choose either a riskier option or a safer one that gives less of a bonus.

You can bring a double-sided cheatsheet into prelims. Prelims are not too hard but there are 3 of them so you have to be consistent.

The final project was really fun — you form a team of up to 4 people and can work on anything you'd like. My team worked on a game and it was super cool being able to integrate OCaml with a GUI.

Overall this class was way more interesting than 2110 and felt less difficult as well to be honest.

subject: CS
course_full: cs 3110 data structures and functional programming
text: This class wasn't bad, but the professors were really boring. I survived solely through Clarkson's textbook and videos. The final project took up a good chunk of time throughout the semester, but it was semi-helpful on my resume. If you're not a CS major, this class is not gonna give you any value.

subject: CS
course_full: cs 3110 data structures and functional programming
text: (Haven't finished the class yet, don't know what grade -- probably an A or A+.) [ Left Out Comment On the Professor], mind-numbing lectures, no idea why this class is regarded as a great course. Changed course from last semester to make it harder, way too much work for such inconsequential material. Unless you're going to a certain firm, you don't need to know OCaml, and in general the programming principles taught are a repeat of 2110 and 2800 (not nearly taught as well) and have no need to take place within the setting of OCaml. No idea why it's core compared to other classes. Destroyed my love for programming, and it's not because the material's hard, either; easy to get full scores on assignments and median+ on exams, but a complete and utter annoyance. If you are deciding between CS and another major, i.e. ORIE/ECE/math etc., you can avoid this class by choosing the other major. Go to school for the love of learning and exploring new domains, not to put yourself through useless drudgery. I do not feel respected as a student with other time-consuming classes and extracurriculars in this class!

subject: CS
course_full: cs 3110 data structures and functional programming
text:
Pretty fun class I think. 

Also had it with Justin Hsu. 

Fun projects - but they did take a long time. OCaml is also a very cool language to learn.

subject: CS
course_full: cs 3110 data structures and functional programming
text: This class taught me that everyone experiences things differently.  I found this class to be hard, with so many exams and projects. I stressed a lot about this class lol. It is a useful class I would say though.

subject: CS
course_full: cs 3110 data structures and functional programming
text: Learned a lot. Amazing content, well-presented and well-structured. Very good stuff

subject: CS
course_full: cs 3110 data structures and functional programming
text: One of my favourite CS courses up to date. The class forces you to think about programming in a new way, and the class is a lot of work but it's 100% worth it.

subject: CS
course_full: cs 3110 data structures and functional programming
text: Clarkson is the GOAT. Hugely passionate professor who cares deeply about his students' learning. The class itself is very well-organized and structured so that you'll see the connections between what you learn from chapter to chapter.  You'll learn so many useful concepts that'll change the way you view programming and this is the class if you want to know if you're a good fit for software engineering.

subject: CS
course_full: cs 3110 data structures and functional programming
text: Great class, really changed my perspective on good programming. Concepts like higher order functions and the inner-workings of data structures like hashmaps and balanced trees were interesting and useful.

subject: CS
course_full: cs 3110 data structures and functional programming
text: Note: I took this class during the semester when there were no exams (SP 21). I thoroughly enjoyed this class, as you get to learn OCaml/functional programming concepts and get to program for all of the assignments. In the end, you get to put a project on your resume that you build from scratch. Clarkson is also a great lecturer, and you learn a lot in addition to just OCaml that reinforces 2110 concepts, how to write good programs, and topics that introduce you to various parts of other fields of CS in the future. If you like programming and computer science, you are sure to like the course.

subject: CS
course_full: cs 3110 data structures and functional programming
text: Textbook is goated. Foster/Hsu were not the best at lecturing but the textbook covers everything nicely. Projects were not too bad and the 24/7 office hours is very helpful.

subject: CS
course_full: cs 3110 data structures and functional programming
text: Clarkson is a really engaging and helpful professor! His lectures are interesting and it taught me a lot about functional programming and programming in general. The assignments are time-consuming though so I would definitely start earlier. Overall, the workload is definitely very heavy,  but rewarding once you learn the material!

subject: CS
course_full: cs 3110 data structures and functional programming
text: Learn OCaml was super interesting and the first half of the course is quite fun coding wise. The stuff about functors and different types of test and test driven development were kind of boring but overall the course was great and clarkson made it enjoyable.

subject: CS
course_full: cs 3110 data structures and functional programming
text: Loved 3110. Clarkson is very passionate about teaching and it shows. Made me fall in love with OCaml and functional programming.

subject: CS
course_full: cs 3110 data structures and functional programming
text: A fair amount of work needed for this class. The assignments take long, and the final project requires a good amount of commitment to create something interesting. I personally had Foster and Hsu when taking the class. Tests are not too hard and are all curved to an 80, so people tend to do well.

subject: CS
course_full: cs 3110 data structures and functional programming
text: Good class, but got kind of confusing towards the end.  If you like coding, this class will be enjoyable for you (hopefully)

subject: CS
course_full: cs 3110 data structures and functional programming
text: The prelims he gave us this year has been pretty difficult but despite that, his videos are very descriptive. The assignments are about 10 hours long to do but its not bad if you start early.

subject: CS
course_full: cs 3110 data structures and functional programming
text: I loved Clarkson! He was very funny and taught very engaging lectures. But the workload was pretty heavy and the class was pretty stressful

subject: CS
course_full: cs 3110 data structures and functional programming
text: Overall a really interesting class that taught me a LOT about recursion + how to learn new langauges + functional programming. Once I got used to Ocaml, it was kind of fun. However, it was a lot of work + pretty stressful.

subject: CS
course_full: cs 3110 data structures and functional programming
text: Took with Foster and Justin Hsu. Their coteaching was hard to follow at times, but overall the class is well organized. The assignments took an average 8-16 hours per two weeks, and the exams were challenging but manageable.  Overall, one of my favorite CS classes I’ve taken here so far!

subject: CS
course_full: cs 3110 data structures and functional programming
text: Clarkson is goated. Ocaml is hard.

subject: CS
course_full: cs 3110 data structures and functional programming
text: One of the most interesting courses I've taken at Cornell. Functional programming is completely different from the OOP that most programmers will be famliar with from previous classes, and the concepts you learn in this course will be really valuable for yeaes to come. OCaml isn't that widely used in the real world but it's useful for learning the key concepts.

subject: CS
course_full: cs 3110 data structures and functional programming
text: clarkson is the best and a great prof, and the work is really interesting, but this class is a lot

subject: CS
course_full: cs 3110 data structures and functional programming
text: I enjoy the class and the content we're learning is pretty interesting. In addition, the professors are super nice and it’s very easy to get help in the class.

subject: CS
course_full: cs 3110 data structures and functional programming
text: If you are not smart, then CS 3110 is good for you because everything has a step-by-step instruction. Otherwise it is not, because once you figure out a better way than what you are instructed to do, you are punished.

subject: CS
course_full: cs 3110 data structures and functional programming
text: Clarkson is fantastic, every lecture is amazing. The assignments are good too, and the team project is fun and very useful for learning how to code a usable project as a team. OCaml is a great language too.

subject: CS
course_full: cs 3110 data structures and functional programming
text: The class was very informative and well-organized, however there was a lot of exams in fall 2021 semester. The coursework did feel a little overwhelming, but most of the staff was very supportive.

subject: CS
course_full: cs 3110 data structures and functional programming
text: I'm not a fan of OCaml, but Clarkson made learning it as painless as possible. The course was very well organized and assignments and grades were very fair. You can tell he cares about his students.

subject: CS
course_full: cs 3110 data structures and functional programming
text: I'm not a big OCaml fan, but Clarkson makes learning it as painless as possible.

subject: CS
course_full: cs 3110 data structures and functional programming
text: Clarkson is a great professor, but the class is challenging. OCaml was hard to get at first, but I do enjoy it now. I also liked the assignments more as they went on, but they can be very time-consuming. Taken Spring 2020. Clarkson definitely values students' opinions and feedback, he even cancelled all exams.

subject: CS
course_full: cs 3110 data structures and functional programming
text: Took during S20 with Foster, who had very fun lectures and explained concepts very well with examples. Had attendance in lecture with icuckers with review questions. Prelims were very difficult and there were programming assignments every week. Course went online after because of covid, and Nate Foster was really accommodating in attendance. Programming assignments take about 10 hours each.

subject: CS
course_full: cs 3110 data structures and functional programming
text: Absolutely loved CS 3110, and after struggling in CS 2110, I found my passion for programming again. You just have to take this with Professor Clarkson - he is quite literally the best. The assignments are difficult, but doable if you start early and use consulting hours a lot. The course content is pretty interesting even though OCaml is kind of a strange language. I didn't have prelims because of COVID so I think the course was a lot less stressful for me too.

subject: CS

subject: CS
course_full: cs 3110 data structures and functional programming
text: BEST CS CLASS (a little bit of an exaggeration) Clarkson is GOAT and he teaches the class really well. OCaml is very different and not intuitive but the class was paced perfectly so that by the last programming assignment we could pull it off in one go. The final project was also great cause we had to code something from the scratch without any starter code.

subject: CS
course_full: cs 3110 data structures and functional programming
text: Clarkson and Foster both do a great job of running this course/are very thoughtful and accommodating. I think the workload is relatively high (compared to the other core CS classes), but manageable? Basically an assignment every two-ish weeks and a final project for the last few weeks, and office hours can be pretty helpful if you can get a spot :)

subject: CS
course_full: cs 3110 data structures and functional programming
text: This course really lives up to its reputation. Despite the unexpected difficulty of an asynchronous class, the courses were incredibly well organized with clean, fancy videos & a information-rich wiki page. I could see that Clarkson was really passionate into what he's teaching, and that passion brought me to appreciate the materials. Since functional programming is a vital tool as a developer, this class also seems like one of the most valuable class in the CS requirements list, too.

subject: CS
course_full: cs 3110 data structures and functional programming
text: To be honest, this class hasn't been very hard this semester, at least nowhere near as bad as the things I've heard. But I think some of that is probably because of COVID. The assignments still take a long time though, especially A3 and A4. But I like how he breaks them up into satisfactory, good, and excellent scope so you can choose how much you want to do. OCaml is pretty easy to pick up, and functional programming is actually kind of nice. Clarkson is pretty good at explaining concepts too, so overall, this class hasn't been bad at all.

subject: CS
course_full: cs 3110 data structures and functional programming
text: The online format is extremely well organized and Professor Michael Clarkson is not only an amazing professor in terms of his ease of understanding and teaching style but extremely passionate and quirky guy. Initially the syntax of Ocaml may be tricky but I learned to love the language. Projects do take a substantial amount of time, so start early!

subject: CS
course_full: cs 3110 data structures and functional programming
text: In recent years they've tried to make this course more streamlined and less work intensive. The year I took it, I found the workload manageable, and the final project was fun (extremely open ended). I felt I learned a lot and the class was the most organized course I've ever taken at Cornell. The professors really care a lot about the material.

subject: CS
course_full: cs 3110 data structures and functional programming
text: The course is hard overall and one of the most challenging and demanding courses I have ever taken. But I also learned a lot.

subject: CS
course_full: cs 3110 data structures and functional programming
text: Love this class! It is a lot of work, but you learn a lot!

subject: CS
course_full: cs 3110 data structures and functional programming
text: Informative course, but a lot of work.

subject: CS
course_full: cs 3110 data structures and functional programming
text: Took S19. Foster makes the class really enjoyable. He goes over examples during class that help solidify the material. People don't read the textbook, but it is very clear and has helpful code snippets. Projects were manageable, but it is very dependent on your partners, which is randomized. Prelims were standard CS exams and he provides practice problems which prepare you pretty well. Concepts are somewhat tricky to grasp at first, but I really enjoyed OCaml once I was familiar with it. It is a different way of thinking which will take a bit of time to get used to.

subject: CS
course_full: cs 3110 data structures and functional programming
text: OCaml is insanely fun. This class is much simpler than 2112 in terms of difficulty but a huge step up from 2110, so be prepared for that. I personally found the course redesign to be fine - coding in groups is something everyone has to learn to do anyways. The exams were quite tricky and the time crunch was real. Overall, one of my favorite CS courses to date. It will change how you approach programming overall, and every other language will feel dirty by the time you're done.

subject: CS
course_full: cs 3110 data structures and functional programming
text: This course was an enormous amount of work, and the content wasn't taught with enough opportunities to practice it to make the difficult exams doable.

subject: CS
course_full: cs 3110 data structures and functional programming
text: I took this class in the Spring of 2019 with Nate Foster. It's a decent workload, but it's nothing you couldn't feasibly do (keep in mind that I took CS 2112 before). The concepts, however, are very interesting and enjoyable to work with, albeit challenging at times. OCaml has definitely changed how I think about programming, and I'm very grateful for the experiences this course gave me.

subject: CS
course_full: cs 3110 data structures and functional programming
text: A time consuming but amazing class if you enjoy programming. Working in OCaml really makes you think about the concepts thought of the course at a high level instead of just one language. I would definitely take, especially in the spring with Foster!

subject: CS
course_full: cs 3110 data structures and functional programming
text: I took it Fall 2018, which I believe is the first semester that Clarkson switched his course to random project groups and weekly assignments (instead of like 2-week ones). Most people I knew agreed that this was a pretty heavy inconvenience because of scheduling concerns with people you don't know and the freeloader problem which Clarkson tried and failed to solve. His change to weekly assignments also makes sure that every week you have to spend a nontrivial amount of time on his assignments which can also be pretty annoying if you're not inherently interested in functional programming. I'm honestly not that interested in programming so a lot of the course was pretty boring for me personally. However, many people I knew found this part interesting so it depends on what you like. The proofs portion of his course was actually kind of interesting in hindsight (but in the moment it seemed like a pain). If you don't spend time trying to understand the course material and do major parts of the projects it will be difficult to get an A. But if you do those things, getting an A seems doable.

subject: CS
course_full: cs 3110 data structures and functional programming
text: I found this class to be very conceptually challenging in a good way. I had a lot of fun with the assignments and felt that I learned a lot

subject: CS
course_full: cs 3110 data structures and functional programming
text: Really well-designed course with great material. The assignments aren't bad but they all have near perfect medians and the exams are brutal so it's hard to beat the median. Still really interesting though due to the class being in OCaml.

subject: CS
course_full: cs 3110 data structures and functional programming
text: Clarkson delivered his promise: I never felt that OOP was soooo elegant until I took this class. It did changed my view of programming. Mutability is sooooo great!

subject: CS
course_full: cs 3110 data structures and functional programming
text: Amazing course. Clarkson loves the material and loves the students in his course. He works very hard to make sure everyone is doing well. The class is hard but it is the weed out for one of the hardest majors at Cornell. And they made the class much easier starting in FA 2018. You have to take this, but just know you'll love it if you love CS.

subject: CS
course_full: cs 3110 data structures and functional programming
text: Course was quite good, Foster was a top-notch professor in Spring 18. Assignments can be difficult but are generally well-designed. Coverage of asynch was a bit shoddy and the section on formal logic/proofs/etc was quite idiotic as is the assignment on Coq (you effectively just try some permutations of simpl, trivial, and auto for half of the problems with some other interspersed commands and you learn nothing, even if you try to do the problems by pure reasoning) in my eyes. Did not attend class but did well, attendance is a very marginal part of the grade. Lecture notes always seemed to be a strict superset of content in lecture and tend to be better organized, so I don't see attendance as being very mandatory.

subject: CS
course_full: cs 3110 data structures and functional programming
text: Yes it's a hard class but very doable with Foster teaching it. Don't stress and overwork yourself trying to get everything perfect or aiming for an A. If you do the labs and do the important part of projects you should do OK on the tests which means you don't need perfect (or even excellent) projects. I loved functional and OCaml. Tons of good content and made me think.

subject: CS
course_full: cs 3110 data structures and functional programming
text: Take this class with Clarkson! It is very very time consuming but all of the projects are really interesting and definitely make you a better coder. The exams are really hard and the projects take legitimately 30 hours even if you go for help. Do not take unless you have to but for CS majors it's a worthwhile class that will make you feel accomplished afterwards. GET A GOOD PARTNER. This class is actually impossible if you have to do everything alone because your partner is a pos.

subject: CS
course_full: cs 3110 data structures and functional programming
text: I took it with Constable -- do not take it with him. Do not. He has no ability to teach, and teaches things that no one cares about. Waste of time except for section, my TAs were fantastic.

subject: CS
course_full: cs 3110 data structures and functional programming
text: Took it as a freshman with Clarkson in fall 2017. It was amazing and it really helped me learn more about programming and myself. That being said, it requires you to be mentally ready to work 30-hour weeks on the assignments. If you're a freshman who's thinking about taking this course, be warned: you'll get put waaaay ahead and it'll teach you a lot, but it's also a tough class that could wreck your gpa and self-esteem

subject: CS
course_full: cs 3110 data structures and functional programming
text: Took this in the fall with Clarkson and had high expectations that were not met. The projects took an unnecessary amount of time and I felt that I could have learned just as much if they had been half as much work. I did improve my programming skills a ton, but this class seriously took up all of my time during the semester.

subject: CS
course_full: cs 3110 data structures and functional programming
text: Difficult. Don't underestimate. Take with clarkson.

subject: CS
course_full: cs 3110 data structures and functional programming
text: It's a hard class for sure, but you will learn a lot. If you pay attention to the high-level ideas, you will learn about programming fundamentals. Also, OCaml is a very cool language and lot of fun to learn.

subject: CS
course_full: cs 3110 data structures and functional programming
text: Clarkson is my hero- a hero that kills me on the inside

subject: CS
course_full: cs 3110 data structures and functional programming
text: This is known to be one of the most challenging courses in the CS core, and probably the least helpful in terms of language-based skills. The course is very project heavy, making it very time consuming. Definitely take with Clarkson.

subject: CS
course_full: cs 3110 data structures and functional programming
text: The first seriously challenging CS class. Definitely take with Clarkson!

subject: CS
course_full: cs 3410 computer system organization and programming
text: There are weekly coding assignments for this course that are definitely QUITE difficult. Also, the professor's lectures are often hard to keep up with and not well-explained. I would definitely say one of the less interesting CS core courses in my opinion, but that's because I'm not really into low-level programming. Learning about assembly is cool, but this course could definitely use work I think.

subject: CS
course_full: cs 3410 computer system organization and programming
text: The course was okay. Worldload was quite tough. Some lectures were good and some were quite confusing. Hakim thought really confusing but Zach was good.

subject: CS
course_full: cs 3410 computer system organization and programming
text: Great class

subject: CS
course_full: cs 3410 computer system organization and programming
text: Prof Guidi was a much better lecturer imo she went slower and explained stuff better. The assignments at first were really hard but better at the end.

subject: CS
course_full: cs 3410 computer system organization and programming
text: Way too many assignments. Not a lot of time to do assignments. It was a hard class but it definitely helped me to discover that I don’t ever want to do system programming as a job.

subject: CS
course_full: cs 3410 computer system organization and programming
text: It covered a wide range of material (and therefore moved pretty quickly), so it was easy to fall behind. At the same time, there were lots of resources on the website that helped me catch up. Some of the projects took a long time, but they were enjoyable.

subject: CS
course_full: cs 3410 computer system organization and programming
text: I took this class in the fall of 2022. Overall, not as bad as I expected. This course is very fast-paced and a lot of this class's content builds upon previously learned material so keeping up is a necessity. Bracy is an excellent lecturer, however, and I don't remember any lecture feeling boring or poorly structured. Because of that, I highly recommend going to lectures despite the slides being posted online. Side note, in my opinion, the recommended prerequisite of CS2024 isn't necessary at all. You'll learn all the C you need during this class.

subject: CS
course_full: cs 3410 computer system organization and programming
text: Definitely the most hours spent in any CS class (for me at least). Towards the end of the course you begin to feel the value of the course material, however the sheer amount of content covered on each exam is dizzying. I enjoyed learning the material but the exams seemed unnecessarily hard. Bracy was a great professor that made the course engaging but she for some reason prides herself on making the exams super hard.

subject: CS
course_full: cs 3410 computer system organization and programming
text: Content is interesting, but everything else is unnecessarily ass.

subject: CS
course_full: cs 3410 computer system organization and programming
text: Pretty bad class - the disconnect between lecture content and assessment/assignment content was pretty insane. Content was pretty interesting though and the professor was great too

subject: CS
course_full: cs 3410 computer system organization and programming
text: This was a very interesting albiet challenging course. Professor Bracy is an excellent lecturer, and articulates hardware concepts very clearly. However, the content becomes much harder after the first prelim and you will have to dedicate a lot of time into learning the material. The projects were interesting (working with Logisim was very annoying but thankfully it is only used for the first two assigments) and Professor Bracy is very generous with slip days (6 for the semester with a maximum of 4 per assignment). Overall, a very difficult course, but I felt like I came out of it learning a lot.

subject: CS
course_full: cs 3410 computer system organization and programming
text: The material of the class is not as hard as you might heard of, but it's surely a lot of new terms/ works. Bracy told us that she normally teaches this in 3 courses at other place but only 1 course at Cornell so it's super fast and a lot of new materials you need to catch up. However, the lab is super helpful in term of exams and assignments.

subject: CS
course_full: cs 3410 computer system organization and programming
text: Taking it Fall 2022. It's a solid amount of work, but the hardest part about the class is the exams. They are generally super long, and require you to have speed and accuracy with all the material. The tests make you think hard about the material and tend to have a couple questions that are extensions to the concepts/examples in class. The projects have been nerfed a bit in the past years, so they are not too hard, and are a great grade booster. The projects are also super cool, and you learn a lot about how a computer works inside and out (you even get to build your own processor and interpreter!). Very cool class, and Bracy was great.

subject: CS
course_full: cs 3410 computer system organization and programming
text: Thought this would be a lot worse than it was, but na it was very interesting. Assignments are very work intensive though, like 10-20 hours on each assignment. Anne Bracy is very good at teaching and the course content is cool.

subject: CS
course_full: cs 3410 computer system organization and programming
text: Really great class with a solid, thorough introduction into the low-level design of computers. Bracy is a nice professor who clearly puts a lot of effort into designing the course and keeping it up to date from semester to semester. The workload can be high particularly with the projects, but if you keep up with the course then the difficulty is very reasonable while being very interesting. Prelims can go over a lot of material and the questions  definitely test your understanding, so it's important to prioritize studying early for this class especially.

subject: CS
course_full: cs 3410 computer system organization and programming
text: Anne Bracy is a great teacher. But the workload was very heavy in the beginning (P1, P2). I honestly just hated and wasn't good at hardware in general so I really didn't like this class.

subject: CS
course_full: cs 3410 computer system organization and programming
text: The workload is very front ended. Project 1 and 2 will be more work than anything else in the class so start early. There is a lot of material and some of it can be difficult. Anne Bracy is a great lecturer!

subject: CS
course_full: cs 3410 computer system organization and programming
text: I really enjoyed this class with Professor Bracy! She made her lectures pretty engaging and I enjoyed learning the content and thought it to be important as the only time I would touch embedded systems most likely. One thing  is that the workload for this class can get kind of high especially earlier on when the projects are difficult especially for those with no experience with embedded.

subject: CS
course_full: cs 3410 computer system organization and programming
text: The material is pretty different from previous cs courses. It's a bit hard to wrap your head around at first, but it gets easier as you go. The professor is very organized and thorough with lectures.

subject: CS
course_full: cs 3410 computer system organization and programming
text: Definitely not as bad as many people make it out to be. Bracy has been my favorite lecturer at Cornell so far, and she made me enjoy something I thought I would hate going into the class. The class has a decent workload, especially with the first two projects. It also was not as well organized as 3110, but still a great class nevertheless.

subject: CS
course_full: cs 3410 computer system organization and programming
text: Took this with Weatherspoon Spring 2020 so it was weird with COVID in the middle. This class was so much work. To be fair, I had absolutely no experience in digital logic prior to this class, so I really struggled in the beginning. Each project took anywhere between 10-20 hours. I think I really learned a lot though, especially since I basically did the second project (RISC-V processor) by myself... but yeah it made my logic skills a lot better. Professor wise, he's really nice but not that great at explaining the concepts.

subject: CS
course_full: cs 3410 computer system organization and programming
text: I took this class with Bracy in fall 2020. Because of COVID-19, the class structure changed a good amount- no partners for assignments, and the pace had to be faster than usual to fit everything in before the prelims. Difficult and takes up a ton of time- the most time-consuming class I've taken at Cornell.

subject: CS
course_full: cs 3410 computer system organization and programming
text: According to Bracy, the course material was adjusted for covid. The course material was interesting and difficult, and the projects were on the harder side in the beginning so prepare for that. Workload definitely went down as the semester went on.

subject: CS
course_full: cs 3410 computer system organization and programming
text: Bracy is a good lecturer, but this class is very fast paced especially towards the middle of the semester. I found myself having to rewatch lectures because some of the concepts would go over my head the first time. The projects are very long and can seem very intimidating at first. The project write ups are also pretty vague which is why I think these assignments are harder than they need to be. Office hours are really crowded the week an assignment is due so start early if you know you're going to need help.

subject: CS
course_full: cs 3410 computer system organization and programming
text: I think the class is painful if you don't come into the class with any knowledge about digital logic/computer architecture. Overconfidence can be a real thing. But I thought the projects that came after the ALU and Mini-RISCV assignments were a lot of fun, I felt like I understood the purpose of this class a lot better after doing them. Weatherspoon doesn't have as much of a cult following as Anne Bracy, his pacing is a bit slow, he's hard to follow often, but at least he's awfully nice and caring. In my experience, if you stick it out in the class long enough you might eventually get to the point where you can understand his lectures better. I think his lectures would definitely benefit from being recorded like they were this semester. Also for Spring 2020 they heavily nerfed the base difficulty of the malloc project and killed the cache project altogether, really shows how nice the course staff is under the pandemic.

subject: CS
course_full: cs 3410 computer system organization and programming
text: I loved this course. Incredibly interesting material if you are like me and previously thought of a computer as a magical box without any sort of idea as to how it works. Professor Bracy is a great lecturer, and the prelims are moderately difficult but fair.

subject: CS
course_full: cs 3410 computer system organization and programming
text: Anne Bracy has fantastic slides, is an amazing lecturer, and really helps you master the material with the structure of the course. Significant workload, but by the end of the course you really feel like you have mastered the material!

subject: CS
course_full: cs 3410 computer system organization and programming
text: I took this class with Anne Bracy in the Fall of 2019. Generally, a solid class - Bracy's wonderful ability to give good lectures helped us understand many concepts with relative ease, and the projects were usually fun to work on. That said, it's a good amount of work - I would guess about 15 hours / week. Office hours and TAs are very helpful here if you get stuck. My one complaint about this class was the lack of a "test harness" to test our code on in a robust manner. I feel like this would have helped me learn a lot more from the projects if I had one.

subject: CS
course_full: cs 3410 computer system organization and programming
text: Took during SP18. It was not as bad as the stories often say, but be prepared to work on several time consuming projects. Even though the projects were hard, you learn a lot. The course staff was great and really helped you out in a pinch.

subject: CS
course_full: cs 3410 computer system organization and programming
text: Nowhere near as bad as some of the horror stories had led me to believe. Projects were quite short and exams had tons of time so that no one ever had problems finishing. That said, the course was not as well organized as classes like 2110, 2112, or 3110, and some projects like buffer overflow probably could've benefited from a few more starter hints. If you played a lot of Minecraft, all your redstone knowledge will unironically help out a ton on the first half of the class. Overall, not the best class, but you'll survive.

subject: CS
course_full: cs 3410 computer system organization and programming
text: Very hard course with very hard prelims and long projects. However, the TAs are for the most part awesome and you learn a lot of pretty interesting material.

subject: CS
course_full: cs 3410 computer system organization and programming
text: Took it with Weatherspoon in Sp '18. While the material is all fairly unfamiliar, it's not super difficult if you do the readings. Projects are pretty time intensive and take a while just to figure out what's going on, but once you get going they're not too bad, and I found them to be pretty rewarding. Malloc is a nightmare, but if you get it working you're pretty much set.

subject: CS
course_full: cs 3410 computer system organization and programming
text: Bracy was a top-notch professor in Fall 17. That being said, the course is sometimes poorly organized and assignments are sometimes nonsensical (i.e. buffer overflow literally tests almost 0% of important course content, Cache Wars which was reintroduced in Spring 18 is an even worse offender on this front). Take it with Bracy, absolutely. Attendance was graded, but attendance to labs is much more valuable than attendance to lectures (but Bracy was a pretty good lecturer).

subject: CS
course_full: cs 3410 computer system organization and programming
text: Material wise it's not too bad until the last few lectures (virtual memory and multicore). Prelims aren't easy but they're doable with enough studying. Project wise, however, it's really challenging, expect to spend plenty of time in overcrowded office hours. The projects take 20-40 hours each and the final (malloc) is a nightmare. If you can get stuff working I guess it could be rewarding, but if you're like me and don't get any of the projects it's not fun and weighs down on you a lot. come in with a strong mindset and maybe you'll get through.

subject: CS
course_full: cs 3410 computer system organization and programming
text: This course is absolutely horrible. Just come into it with a strong mindset and you will get out - but just know that the material will make you question the major.

subject: CS
course_full: cs 3410 computer system organization and programming
text: Anne Bracy is honestly awesome and the course material was relatively interesting. There are plenty of ways to save your grade from low exam scores or a messed up project. If you took 3110 and hated it you will probably like 3410 better. If you liked 3110 odds are you will potentially not be as interested in the 3410 material. SUPER time consuming. I think spending 20 hours straight at office hours for MIPS and the final project are rites of passage for CS majors. Definitely prepared me well for other CS classes but not for the faint of heart.

subject: CS
course_full: cs 3410 computer system organization and programming
text: Worst experience of my entire life. Take the ECE 2300/3140 sequence and save yourself a lot of pain.

subject: CS
course_full: cs 3410 computer system organization and programming
text: The difficulty of this class is heavily overstated - yes, it's a solid amount of work, but concepts are not super difficult if you actually try to learn the material instead of flounder around. Everything is graded pretty leniently and they give you a ton of room to make up points with participation through readings and iClicker. Also, a project will have you putting in 30 hours but you have 2 weeks for it so what's the big deal?

subject: CS
course_full: cs 3410 computer system organization and programming
text: This class is without a doubt, the hardest I've taken at Cornell--and will probably be the hardest I will take. However, the TA staff is amazing and people are always answering piazza posts at any time of night (yes, even at 2am). Additionally, I personally found Bracy to be an excellent lecturer. She has a talent for taking complex ideas and presenting them in simpler ways. Also, her powerpoints are very well done with very helpful animations. I highly suggest not skipping any of her classes so you can see the full effects of the powerpoints. The projects are difficult, and you can NOT start them two days before and expect to finish them (unless you're a coding genius). To truly get the most you can out of this class, I suggest 1. going to office hours whenever you are even slightly confused 2. getting a study group and 3. perhaps take an easier courseload. It's two semesters of material in one semester, so get ready to grind.

subject: CS
course_full: cs 3410 computer system organization and programming
text: This class packs a lot of information into just one semester, but Bracy is very sympathetic and understands how demanding the class is. Although the projects and tests were challenging, in hindsight this was one of the most fair and rewarding CS classes I have taken.

subject: CS
course_full: cs 3410 computer system organization and programming
text: Horrible class. Anne Bracy is a unbelievably disorganized professor and unhelpful. If you're looking to do well in this class, make sure to have a lot of time to spend as the course staff and Professor aren't willing to help.

subject: CS
course_full: cs 3410 computer system organization and programming
text: Things have apparently changed, but as taught by Weatherspoon this was my worst experience in the entire CS major. Pacing was erratic and full of his personal interests (or simple bragging, to be less generous). Scheduled review classes didn't happen. The material covered on the test tracked the book, but the lectures frequently missed essential content - and were required (via iClicker questions) anyway. It eventually proved better to sit at the back and study from an eBook. A genuinely miserable experience; find another professor or take 3420 if necessary.

subject: CS
course_full: cs 3410 computer system organization and programming
text: Bracy is a good lecturer, but the class literally packs CS 2300 and CS 3420 into one semester.  You learn a lot, but often times the pace is too fast for comfort.  Overall, the class was difficult, more so because of the heavy workload than the actual difficulty of the material (although it is also challenging).  For anyone taking the class, I would suggest 1) Starting projects early  2) Going to office hours.  The TAs are legendary

subject: CS
course_full: cs 3410 computer system organization and programming
text: this class might be hard but you learn so much. i went into the class debating between majoring in infosci or CS, but after it was over I was sure I was a CS major. the projects are pretty interesting and bracy is amazing. also, seeing your finished MIPS32 processor will make you feel so satisfied. i didnt think the class was impossibly hard, but you definitely need to start things with time to spare.  i think the main complaint is workload rather than difficulty

subject: CS
course_full: cs 3410 computer system organization and programming
text: Anne bracy is awesome!

subject: CS
course_full: cs 3410 computer system organization and programming
text: The course covers a lot of material very quickly. As long as you make an effort to pay attention each class and review consistently the prelims shouldn't be a problem. Projects are time consuming and should be started as soon as possible.

subject: CS
course_full: cs 3410 computer system organization and programming
text: Bracy is great at teaching, comes well prepared, and has tons of info (the slides go by really fast). Prelim questions are out of the blue and assignments take a long time. Be sure to grab a good partner.

subject: CS
course_full: cs 4410 operating systems
text: Try to take it in the spring with RVR. He is the goat professor. Really kind. Really smart. Really quirky and nerdy. His exams are much easier compared to others.

subject: CS
course_full: cs 4410 operating systems
text:
Definitely take this with RVR. I highly recommend reading OSTEP before the lectures. The content is very interesting and if you have a good understanding of it it makes preparing for exams easy. I took CS 3420 4 years prior and managed to do well thanks to this book and taking notes during lectures. 

The exams were usually T/F and then a few long questions that make you think. This was way easier than Alvisi’s exams where you have to memorize all the steps when an interrupt or context switch occurs. The grading was very fair and generous.

Homeworks are not too hard and can usually be finished in a day or two by going to office hours. Programming assignments could be challenging mainly because of the learning curve with harmony.  My favorite was the last one since it was a little more open ended.

subject: CS
course_full: cs 4410 operating systems
text: Material is interesting but Alvisi teaches it in a more general manner while the exams can become very specific. He's a fun lecturer though.   Half of the class is concurrency and the other half is about operating systems itself. Programming assignments are entirely about concurrency, if you want to implement some of the operating system stuff then do the OS practicum.

subject: CS
course_full: cs 4410 operating systems
text: Mediocre lecturer. Students had to fight to get practice exams even though there was very little study material. Once we were given actual material to prep with, class became much more manageable. Projects were easy and were similar to examples in the textbook, but feedback on code is obfuscated and is just computer generated outputs.

subject: CS
course_full: cs 4410 operating systems
text: The content is very interesting. Great professor who explains things really well but content itself is really tricky and like the assignments: can be difficult to think clearly about

subject: CS
course_full: cs 4410 operating systems
text: Lorenzo seems to be very passionate about teaching the subject, however sometimes the lectures are very slow and can be difficult to follow. For studying I find it best to read the harmony and 3EP textbook as I find it is better than looking at the slides. The first prelim was super difficult / unfair but he graded nicer than expected.

subject: CS
course_full: cs 4410 operating systems
text: Content is theoretically interesting, especially since I liked 3410 and this class is a good tie in to how the hardware is important relative to the software, but Lorenzo Alvisi is just a boring lecturer. He often rambles on and on and it's hard to tell if what he's saying is relevant to the current topic at hand or even how it could relate. He's just not really engaging. Also, the exams are somewhat difficult given the little practice that we get to do. The only upside is not having a lot of work to do (so far into the semester, we had three programming assignments and three short homeworks that were all autograded), but that comes at a cost of feeling not prepared for the exams when they come.

subject: CS
course_full: cs 4410 operating systems
text: Professor Lorenzo is very kind and caring! However, the course was not very organized with the contents and the exams were extremely difficult.

subject: CS
course_full: cs 4410 operating systems
text: RVR is a great professor--decent lecturer, good at organizing the class material, and especially his revamping of the class with Harmony makes it a totally different beast. 5-6 written psets, 3 programming assignments (nontrivial but not particularly involved, more about precise coding than volume of code). The content is interesting and some of the most practical information you can learn in CS, even though it may not be directly applicable.

subject: CS
course_full: cs 4410 operating systems
text: Took it with RVR. The class material was fairly boring, but the prof tries to make it interesting. Mostly multithreading topics rather than actual os topics. Prelims weren't too hard, but there's no curve so it might get in the way of your grade even if you have low medians. Grade was split 50/50 homework and prelims.

subject: CS
course_full: cs 4410 operating systems
text: Not too bad for a CS class, but reading the textbook and going to office hours is very important. Not much practice available for prelims, and something class explanations are not super clear.

subject: CS
course_full: cs 4410 operating systems
text: Almost weekly problem sets (every 10 days). Can be tricky, but office hours are very helpful. Class itself is super interesting topics and overall pretty easy. Taken with Kleinberg and Levy.

subject: CS
course_full: cs 4410 operating systems
text: RVR is a nice prof and tries his best but the course content is really boring imo and feels like memorizing bits of trivia.

subject: CS
course_full: cs 4410 operating systems
text: I think Renesse's lectures are a bit convoluted. He often talks in circles but it is nothing unbearable. I can definitely tell he has passion for the course which I appreciate. I also think that the psets are really easy but that does make prelims a lot more difficult.

subject: CS
course_full: cs 4410 operating systems
text: OK course

subject: CS
course_full: cs 4410 operating systems
text: Professor was VERY nice, but course staff was really lacking. The exams were super hard. We got promised a few things that we never got (review session for prelim 1, practice exam) and we had to go begging on Ed to get our answers back for prelim 2 the day before the final.

subject: CS
course_full: cs 4410 operating systems
text: Rachit made the class really fun and lectures went over many design choices, but was boring sometimes since that is just how OS is. It is not much work compared to other CS classes, just 5 HWs.

subject: CS
course_full: cs 4410 operating systems
text: Not the world's most engaging material to me at least, but it was presented well enough and the assignments and exams were all fairly short and intuitive. I suspect that it may be harder with different professors, but with Rachit Agarwal I wouldn't worry.

subject: CS
course_full: cs 4410 operating systems
text: I couldn't understand most of the materials in the lectures. Memorize all the things for the exams, and forget them afterwards very quickly.

subject: CS
course_full: cs 4410 operating systems
text: kind of a silly, scattered course, lots of trivia. assignments full of repetitive trivia that didn't prepare me on the exams, but I did alright on the math/coding parts.   some of the topics were more interesting than others. OS is not super relevant to what I plan to do, but some of it is nice background knowledge.   I appreciate RVR's efforts; he seems nice and has put up some great course infrastructure - invented a programming language and a PDF autograder just for us :)      he moves a little fast though and I always feel drained after 75 nonstop minutes of note-taking, more so than for other classes.    (This course was taken online during the pandemic)

subject: CS
course_full: cs 4410 operating systems
text: Easiest core CS class by far, which is not saying much because  of how crushingly hard Algo and the others are. Rvr removed Piazza for this semester, which has been awful.  We did get study groups that we could talk about the HW with but they were either unresponsive or we ran into questions about clarification that Piazza would have solved. Problem sets were fill in the blank PDF's autograded, so while you could request regrades it made homeworks more stressful. The material itself was interesting, and I think it's super important to know if you want to do software. Rvr also invented a concurrent programming language that I first saw as a Walmart Python but later saw itseld usefulness in programming assignments.

subject: CS
course_full: cs 4410 operating systems
text: Very hard exams, lecture material isn't very helpful for starting projects, poorly written projects, and subjective grading. Many projects can't be efficiently tested, so they can take a long time to complete and be extremely stressful. The one redeeming factor is that professor Alvisi is quite kind in person.

subject: CS
course_full: cs 4410 operating systems
text: Probably the easiest class of the CS major. Only three assignments, and they drop your lowest exam grade. It's kind of a double edged sword, though, since screwing up even one assignment can tank your grade. RVR and Schneider co-taught this course when I took it. RVR was super friendly and fairly engaging as a lecturer but it very quickly becomes clear that he has a ton of expertise in a very narrow range of fields, and whenever he needs to step out of that circle, he'll frequently trip over himself and get things wrong. Schneider, on the other hand, is a jerk, and delivers lectures with such a stupendous amount of dryness that I'd frequently find myself zoning out within minutes of lecture starting, despite spending concentrated effort to pay attention. The course is pretty poorly run and disorganized, and the policy of cancelling all office hours and blacking out Piazza starting 48 hours before any exam was baffling to all. Easiest course in the CS core, but probably also the worst.

subject: CS
course_full: cs 4410 operating systems
text: Very easy class but tedious to take - projects and exams are a waste of time, but you just have to get through it

subject: CS
course_full: cs 4410 operating systems
text: Took it with lorenzo, great lecturer and he cares a lot about the class. He goes more in depth on fewer topics which made the tests really hard (and hard to study for) but if you're ok with that then it's worth taking. Projects were kind of hard but better than 3410. Really liked the course

subject: CS
course_full: cs 4410 operating systems
text: Horrible course, really made me hate the CS major.

subject: CS
course_full: cs 4410 operating systems
text: Tough exams but they reduced number of projects

subject: CS
course_full: cs 4410 operating systems
text: Without the practicum this class is pretty easy. The assignments are mostly trivial and the concepts are mostly intuitive but the exam questions still require memorization.

subject: CS
course_full: cs 4410 operating systems
text: I took the class in Fall 2018 with Professor Van Renesse. I was positively impressed with how nice the Professor was and how he cared about the students. In terms of content, I heard that the class was easier this semester compared to previous semesters. In my experience it was definitely easier and less time consuming compared to CS 3410 and CS 3110, but it can vary from person to person. There were only 3 assignments, 3 paper reviews of 300 words each (which were not very demanding) and 3 exams which definitely required a good amount of preparation.

subject: CS
course_full: cs 4410 operating systems
text: This class seems easy coming off of it's prereq of 3410 since there are only 4 projects but watch out. The exams were written with trick questions and the networking project is an actual nightmare. Projects 1, 2, and 4 are usually the same every year and not bad but project 3 will literally crater your grade if you don't work on it for hours on end. The final is optional but you should take it unless you have an A in the class because a ton of people choose to take it to replace a prelim grade and the median in the class always goes up because of it. My year they used grade deflation too. CS majors you have to take it so oh well but otherwise just don't. and whatever you do DON'T TAKE THE PRAC. Unless you like torture.

subject: CS
course_full: cs 4410 operating systems
text: Fall 2017 with Sirer and Bracey. As a lecturer, Sirer would often go on tangents which made it feel like he had no lecture plans. Also there was 1 project where there was a lot of confusion on the specifications. And grading was slow. Overall this class felt like a mess

subject: CS
course_full: cs 4410 operating systems
text: The course varies significantly from professor to professor, but under Prof. Agarwal it was absolutely awful.  Poorly thought out assignments with no feedback (or useless feedback), projects that the TAs and staff did not even understand, and lectures that taught absolutely nothing.  I cannot stress this enough: under Agarwal, this was literally the *worst* course I ever took at Cornell.

subject: ECE
course_full: ece 2300 digital logic and computer organization
text: He was very good at explaining concepts but lectures could feel very long and boring at times. Decent workload with a PSET and lab due most weeks but definitely manageable. Course content was difficult conceptually but exams were very fair.

subject: ECE
course_full: ece 2300 digital logic and computer organization
text: Interesting and engaging lecturer. Workload was high solely because of the labs, but the end result was cool. Best computer engineering course I've taken so far.

subject: ECE
course_full: ece 2300 digital logic and computer organization
text: It is so much more work than I expected. Not an easy class. I regret taking it.

subject: ECE
course_full: ece 2300 digital logic and computer organization
text: David is a very kind professor. Goes kind of fast, but the concepts are easy and manageable.

subject: ECE
course_full: ece 2300 digital logic and computer organization
text: Zhiru Zhang is a very good professor. He makes very good videos that if you missed lectures, you can still learn the materials based of his videos. Overall, despite the decent workload he gives you, its worth taking this class

subject: ECE
course_full: ece 2300 digital logic and computer organization
text: Great professor. Class was somewhat challenging but extremely rewarding and very logic based. The only thing was that labs do take time, especially towards the end of the year.

subject: ECE
course_full: ece 2300 digital logic and computer organization
text: I enjoyed the class. Zhang is a pretty solid and well-organized lecturer. The labs were manageable as long as you are time efficient. There were plenty of office hours so it was very easy to get help!

subject: ECE
course_full: ece 2300 digital logic and computer organization
text: Pretty solid class with material really well explained in the lectures. A lot of ways to practice for tests. The labs are kinda long and sometimes annoying, but it is definitely an class to take that is not too hard.

subject: ECE
course_full: ece 2300 digital logic and computer organization
text: Much harder than the class was with Albonesi, according to friends. Zhang is a great lecturer, but having three assignments a week at times, averaging to 2 assignments due every week (lab+pset) was really a lot.

subject: ECE
course_full: ece 2300 digital logic and computer organization
text: Took during S20 with Edward Suh. He explains the topics well but lectures may be dry with later concepts. Homeworks are not that hard to do with lecture material, and labs might take a long time, and verilog is just bad. Exams are very fair and reviewing homework and past prelims is very helpful. Good introduction to ECE if you have never taken something similar. Do not take this class after Wines or you will fall asleep every time.

subject: ECE
course_full: ece 2300 digital logic and computer organization
text: The class is not hard, but it's definitely not easy either. Professor Albonesi goes through the lecture material pretty fast, but you can easily review the stuff afterward. The weekly homework can have mildly challenging problems and the labs in the second half of the semester can take a long time to debug. However, going to office hours for labs helps a lot, but you would need to start the labs early, or else the office hours are usually very crowded. The random partners for labs can be very annoying if you don't get paired with someone good. But exams are easy if you just do the practice ones they give you.

subject: ECE
course_full: ece 2300 digital logic and computer organization
text: I took it with Professor Albonesi. Lectures are a bit long, but he's really good at answering questions. Also is very understanding about Covid and spread out assignments after students have suggested it on Piazza. I think labs can be tough, but TAs are pretty helpful at debugging (which takes the longest).

subject: ECE
course_full: ece 2300 digital logic and computer organization
text: Albonesi is an awesome professor whose lectures are pretty thorough, and he's always opening to answering lots of questions and clarifying topics during lecture. The way he and the course staff handled course organization and logistics during COVID-19 was pretty considerate and caring towards students (open note for two prelims and a final, lots of practice prelims). There's a good amount of work (weekly psets and labs) but nothing that I ever felt was busy work or unnecessary.  Overall, a good class!

subject: ECE
course_full: ece 2300 digital logic and computer organization
text: I am currently taking this class and if you are a CS major like me who is trying to just get a requirement out of the way, it can be hard to enjoy this class. It's definitely out of scope and I'm still learning to appreciate the material. The lecture slides are really comprehensive but his lectures are a bit monotonous. Labs are worth 30% of our grade which is greater than our prelims which are 20% each. But they TAKE FOREVER. There have been weeks were we had something due 4 different days of the week which is kind of absurd. However, he is super understanding and after some complaints, he spread the assignments out more. The prelims are also very similar to the practice he gives you and are pretty fair but they don't give great partial credit. I'm taking it fall 2020 and the exams were in person open note which really REALLY helps. I would suspect that without notes this class would be mostly memorization. Overall the class is okay and the prof is pretty cool!

subject: ECE
course_full: ece 2300 digital logic and computer organization
text: The prof goes through lectures extremely fast and it was hard to keep up with the material. The good thing about online classes is that I can always watch the recordings later. The worst thing is that we don't get to choose our own lab groups. My first partner always pushes off the meeting time we had previously settled on. My second partner either doesn't do what he promised to do what does them the very last minute. I ended up doing most of the labs by myself.

subject: ECE
course_full: ece 2300 digital logic and computer organization
text: Test questions did not reflect the difficulty of HWs and lectures are incomprehensible if you do not do the corresponding readings.

subject: ECE
course_full: ece 2300 digital logic and computer organization
text: Took this with Edward Suh Spring 20. Without considering the whole covid situation, I personally didn't really like the class. The content was alright, but Prof Suh didn't really organize the class very well in my opinion. Some TAs were great (mostly the undergraduate ones), but I didn't find the graduate TAs helpful. Labs were long, but understandably so (but don't take it from me, I only had 2 labs that were in person). The first prelim was really easy, but the take home ones afterwards (covid) were really really hard.

subject: ECE
course_full: ece 2300 digital logic and computer organization
text: Took it with Albonesi Fall 20. The class had lectures that explained the processor really well. The lab, especially the last 2, were long.

subject: ECE
course_full: ece 2300 digital logic and computer organization
text: Pretty difficult for CS majors and requires a good amount of memorization for the exams. Labs can be difficult if you're stuck with a bad partner, and office hours lines can get pretty long.

subject: ECE
course_full: ece 2300 digital logic and computer organization
text: Test questions are formed from lectures slides, so make sure to look at the smallest of questions on the slides because they usually end up being on prelims. Homework questions work the same way. I found homework to be way way easier when I was ahead in the class material. Labs suck a lot if you have a bad, unwilling group. Ended up doing most of them on my  own and not going to lab sections.

subject: ECE
course_full: ece 2300 digital logic and computer organization
text: Took in fall 2017 with David Albonesi. The content is not difficult at all, but Albonesi has a soothing voice and it's easy to fall asleep in class sometimes. Lecture slides are good quality and quite easy to understand. Homeworks aren't particularly difficult, but labs can be quite time consuming. The assigned textbook is generally great supplementary material. Exams are crammable as well.
